# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albert-w-bally
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albert-w-bally/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:albert-w-bally/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:albert-w-bally/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:albert-w-bally/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The **American Association of Petroleum Geologists** (**AAPG**) is one of the world's largest professional geological societies with about 17,000 members across 129 countries.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Over the years, the activities of the AAPG have broadened so that they bring together not just geology but also geophysics, geochemistry, engineering, and innovative analytics to enable the more efficient and environmentally-friendly approaches to the development of all earth-based energy sources.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] New transformative technologies, such as the ability to better characterize reservoirs through imaging and the integration of multiple data sources, are coupled with concerns about the environment.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Members and affiliated societies are very much involved in preserving the quality of groundwater, dealing responsibly with produced water, and understanding the mechanisms of induced seismicity.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In addition to subsurface investigations, the society supports mapping of the surface and the use of new technologies (UAVs, drones, big data analytics), with the goals of advancing the science and understanding of geological processes.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG publishes the *AAPG Explorer* magazine and *AAPG Bulletin* scientific journal, and co-publishes a scientific journal with the Society of Exploration Geophysicists called *Interpretation*.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The organization holds an annual meeting including a technical conference and exhibition, sponsors other conferences and continuing education for members around the world such as ongoing Geosciences Technology Workshops, and provides various other services to its members.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The organization also includes divisions focused on particular aspects of the profession.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] These include the Division of Environmental Geosciences, Division of Professional Affairs, and the Energy and Minerals Division.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The association membership has included Harrison "Jack" Schmitt, a U.S. astronaut who walked on the Moon.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] At its annual conventions and international conferences AAPG recognizes the distinguished contributions in the field of petroleum geosciences with various awards, including the Sidney Powers Memorial Award, Michel T.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Halbouty Outstanding Leadership Award, Grover E.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Murray Memorial Distinguished Educator Award, Wallace Pratt Memorial Award, and Ziad Rafiq Beydoun Memorial Award.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG IBA award is given immediately following the IBA competition that is held at that year's annual convention.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG promotes student involvement in the profession by holding an annual Imperial Barrel Award competition where geoscience graduate students are encouraged to explore a career in the energy industry.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In this global competition, university teams analyze a dataset (geology, geophysics, land, production infrastructure, and other relevant materials) and deliver their results in a 25-minute presentation.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The students' presentations are judged by industry experts, providing the students a real-world, career-development experience.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] IBA offers students and their faculty advisor a chance to win accolades for themselves and cash prizes for their schools, and winning teams travel free to the annual AAPG convention to network with both future colleagues and future employers.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The Correlation of Stratigraphic Units of North America (COSUNA) was a project of the AAPG which resulted in the publication of sixteen correlation charts depicting modern concepts of the stratigraphy of North America.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG has supported the investigation of the earth, and over the years, ideas about how oil is formed have changed.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In the 1960s, the AAPG supported the then-revolutionary idea of plate tectonics (vs. isostasy), and looked at plate tectonics as a key to the evolution of basins, and thus the formation of oil and gas.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] An example is Tanya Atwater's work on plate tectonics.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] As a whole, women geoscientists have played an important role in the AAPG's 100-year history as scientists and leaders.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Since that time, the AAPG has worked closely with scientific organizations such as the USGS to apply new scientific breakthroughs to the generation, migration, and entrapment of oil and gas.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The results have brought new understanding of ultra-deepwater reservoirs (such as off the coast of Brazil).
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG has supported geomechanics in order to be able to predict pore pressure and avoid drilling hazards.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The AAPG has also been supportive of investigations having to do with the impact of policies of disposing of produced water by injecting it into deep formations.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Workshops and forums have been held since 2009 (Geosciences Technology Workshops) to analyze the problems and to discuss solutions.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] They have been held throughout the world, and are documented through the presentations.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The presentations from the workshops have been made available for free via the AAPG's open access online journal, Search and Discovery.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] In 2006, the AAPG was criticized for selecting author Michael Crichton for their Journalism Award for *Jurassic Park* and "for his recent science-based thriller *State of Fear*", in which Crichton exposed his rejection of scientific evidence for anthropogenic global warming.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Schrag, a geochemist who directs the Harvard University Center for the Environment, called the award "a total embarrassment" that he said "reflects the politics of the oil industry and a lack of professionalism" on the association's part.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The criticism drew attention to the AAPG's 1999 position statement formally rejecting the likelihood of human influence on recent climate.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] Acknowledging that the association's previous policy statement on Climate Change was "not supported by a significant number of our members and prospective members", AAPG's formal stance was reviewed and changed in July 2007.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] The new statement formally accepts human activity as at least one contributor to carbon dioxide increase, but does not confirm its link to climate change, saying its members are "divided on the degree of influence that anthropogenic CO2 has" on climate.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG also withdrew its earlier criticism of other scientific organizations and research stating, "Certain climate simulation models predict that the warming trend will continue, as reported through NAS, AGU, AAAS, and AMS.
[src:albert-w-bally/american-association-of-petroleum-geologists] AAPG respects these scientific opinions but wants to add that the current climate warming projections could fall within well-documented natural variations in past climate and observed temperature data.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] The **Geological Society of America** (**GSA**) is a nonprofit organization dedicated to the advancement of the geosciences.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] The society was founded in Ithaca, New York, in 1888 by Alexander Winchell, John J.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] Procter and Edward Orton and has been headquartered at 3300 Penrose Place, Boulder, Colorado, US, since 1967.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] GSA began with 100 members under its first president, James Hall.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] In 1889 Mary Emilie Holmes became its first female member.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] It grew slowly but steadily to 600 members until 1931, when a nearly $4 million endowment from 1930 president R.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] As of December 2017, GSA had more than 25,000 members in over 100 countries.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] The society has six regional sections in North America, three interdisciplinary interest groups, and eighteen specialty divisions.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] The stated mission of GSA is "to advance geoscience research and discovery, service to society, stewardship of Earth, and the geosciences profession".
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] Its main activities are sponsoring scientific meetings and publishing scientific literature, particularly the peer-reviewed journals *Geological Society of America Bulletin*, published continuously since 1889, and *Geology*, published since 1973.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] In 2005, GSA introduced its online-only journal *Geosphere*, and in February 2009, GSA began publishing *Lithosphere* (both also peer-reviewed).
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] *Geosphere* and *Lithosphere* are open access as of 2018.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] GSA's monthly news and science magazine, *GSA Today*, is also open access online.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] GSA also publishes three book series: *Special Papers*, *Memoirs*, and *Field Guides*.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] A third major activity is awarding research grants to graduate students.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] GSA issues Position Statements "in support of and consistent with the GSA's Vision and Mission to develop consensus on significant professional, technical, and societal issues of relevance to the geosciences community.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] The Geological Society of America (GSA) supports the scientific conclusions that Earth's climate is changing; the climate changes are due in part to human activities; and the probable consequences of the climate changes will be significant and blind to geopolitical boundaries.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] Furthermore, the potential implications of global climate change and the time scale over which such changes will likely occur require active, effective, long-term planning.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-america] While the precise magnitude and rate of climate change cannot be predicted with absolute certainty, significant change will affect the planet and stress its inhabitants.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] The **Geological Society of London**, known commonly as the **Geological Society**, is a learned society based in the United Kingdom.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] It is the oldest national geological society in the world and the largest in Europe, with more than 12,000 Fellows.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] Fellows are entitled to the postnominal **FGS** (Fellow of the Geological Society), over 2,000 of whom are Chartered Geologists (CGeol).
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] The Society is a registered charity, no.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] It is also a member of the Science Council, and is licensed to award Chartered Scientist to qualifying members.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] The mission of the society is: "Making geologists acquainted with each other, stimulating their zeal, inducing them to adopt one nomenclature, facilitating the communication of new facts and ascertaining what is known in their science and what remains to be discovered".
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] The Society was founded on 13 November 1807 at the Freemasons' Tavern, Great Queen Street, in the Covent Garden district of London.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] It was partly the outcome of a previous club known as the Askesian Society.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] There were 13 founder members: William Babington, James Parkinson, Humphry Davy, George Bellas Greenough, Arthur Aikin, William Allen, Jacques Louis, Comte de Bournon, Richard Knight, James Laird, James Franck, William Haseldine Pepys, Richard Phillips, and William Phillips.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] It received its royal charter on 23 April 1825 from George IV.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] Since 1874, the Society has been based at Burlington House, Piccadilly, London.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] This building houses the Society's library, which contains more than 300,000 volumes of books and journals.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] It is a member of the UK Science Council.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] In 1907 a decision was made by the Society to admit women as Associates, under the condition they distinguished themselves as geological investigators or submitted their own original research.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] Women were first allowed to become Fellows of the Society in 1919.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] Margaret Crosfield became the first, due to alphabetical primacy, of the first eight women to be elected Fellows of the Society, on 21 May 1919.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] In 1991, the Society merged with the Institution of Geologists, which had been formed in 1977 to represent the geological profession.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] The Society is a member of the European Federation of Geologists.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] The Society celebrated its bicentenary in 2007.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] It ran programmes in the geosciences in Britain and abroad, under the auspices of the science writer and palaeontologist Professor Richard Fortey, the president that year.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] The Society has 24 specialist groups and 15 regional groups which serve as an opportunity for those with specific interests to meet and discuss their subject or region.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] They are all free for members to join and some are open to non-members.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] The society publishes two of its own journals, the (formerly *Quarterly*) *Journal of the Geological Society* and the *Quarterly Journal of Engineering Geology & Hydrogeology*.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] It also publishes the magazine *Geoscientist* for Fellows, and has a share in *Geology Today*, published by Wiley.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] It also co-publishes journals and publishes on behalf of other organisations.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] The society counts many famous geologists amongst its past presidents.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] These include pioneers of geology William Buckland, Adam Sedgwick, Roderick Impey Murchison, Charles Lyell, Henry Thomas De la Beche, Thomas Henry Huxley, Joseph Prestwich, Archibald Geikie, Jethro Teall, and Charles Lapworth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] Later well-known names include Alfred Harker, Arthur Elijah Trueman, Herbert Harold Read, Frederick Shotton, and Janet Watson.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] In 1831, it began issuing an annual scientific award for geology, known as the Wollaston Medal.
[src:albert-w-bally/geological-society-of-london] This is still the Society's premier medal, which in 2006 was awarded to James Lovelock, the originator of the Gaia hypothesis.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geology describes the structure of the Earth on and beneath its surface and the processes that have shaped that structure.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geologists study the mineralogical composition of rocks in order to get insight into their history of formation.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geology determines the relative ages of rocks found at a given location; geochemistry (a branch of geology) determines their absolute ages.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] By combining various petrological, crystallographic, and paleontological tools, geologists are able to chronicle the geological history of the Earth as a whole.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] One aspect is to demonstrate the age of the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geology provides evidence for plate tectonics, the evolutionary history of life, and the Earth's past climates.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geologists broadly study the properties and processes of Earth and other terrestrial planets.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geologists use a wide variety of methods to understand the Earth's structure and evolution, including fieldwork, rock description, geophysical techniques, chemical analysis, physical experiments, and numerical modelling.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In practical terms, geology is important for mineral and hydrocarbon exploration and exploitation, evaluating water resources, understanding natural hazards, remediating environmental problems, and providing insights into past climate change.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geology is a major academic discipline, and it is central to geological engineering and plays an important role in geotechnical engineering.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The majority of geological data comes from research on solid Earth materials.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Meteorites and other extraterrestrial natural materials are also studied by geological methods.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Minerals are naturally occurring elements and compounds with a definite homogeneous chemical composition and an ordered atomic arrangement.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Amorphous substances that resemble a mineral are sometimes referred to as mineraloids, although there are exceptions such as georgeite and autunite.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Some amorphous substances formed by geological processes are considered minerals if the original substance was a mineral before metamictisation.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Each mineral has distinct physical properties, and there are many tests to determine each of them.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Minerals are often identified through these tests.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] A rock is any naturally occurring solid mass or aggregate of minerals or mineraloids.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Most research in geology is associated with the study of rocks, as they provide the primary record of the majority of the geological history of the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] There are three major types of rock: igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The rock cycle illustrates the relationships among them (see diagram).
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] When a rock solidifies or crystallizes from melt (magma or lava), it is an igneous rock.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The active flow of molten rock is closely studied in volcanology, and igneous petrology aims to determine the history of igneous rocks from their original molten source to their final crystallization.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Rocks can be weathered and eroded, then redeposited and lithified into a sedimentary rock.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Sedimentary rocks are mainly divided into four categories: sandstone, shale, carbonate, and evaporite.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This group of classifications focuses partly on the size of sedimentary particles (sandstone and shale), and partly on mineralogy and formation processes (carbonation and evaporation).
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Igneous and sedimentary rocks can then be turned into metamorphic rocks by heat and pressure that change its mineral content, resulting in a characteristic fabric.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] All three types may melt again, and when this happens, new magma is formed, from which an igneous rock may once again solidify.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Organic matter, such as coal, bitumen, oil, and natural gas, is linked mainly to organic-rich sedimentary rocks.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] To study all three types of rock, geologists evaluate the minerals of which they are composed and their other physical properties, such as texture and fabric.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geologists study unlithified materials (referred to as *superficial deposits*) that lie above the bedrock.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This study is often known as Quaternary geology, after the Quaternary period of geologic history, which is the most recent period of geologic time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In the 1960s, it was discovered that the Earth's lithosphere, which includes the crust and rigid uppermost portion of the upper mantle, is separated into tectonic plates that move across the plastically deforming, solid, upper mantle, which is called the asthenosphere.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This theory is supported by several types of observations, including seafloor spreading and the global distribution of mountain terrain and seismicity.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] There is an intimate coupling between the movement of the plates on the surface and the convection of the mantle (that is, the heat transfer caused by the slow movement of ductile mantle rock).
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Thus, oceanic parts of plates and the adjoining mantle convection currents always move in the same direction – because the oceanic lithosphere is actually the rigid upper thermal boundary layer of the convecting mantle.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This coupling between rigid plates moving on the surface of the Earth and the convecting mantle is called plate tectonics.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The development of plate tectonics has provided a physical basis for many observations of the solid Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Plate tectonics has provided a mechanism for Alfred Wegener's theory of continental drift, in which the continents move across the surface of the Earth over geological time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] They provided a driving force for crustal deformation, and a new setting for the observations of structural geology.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The power of the theory of plate tectonics lies in its ability to combine all of these observations into a single theory of how the lithosphere moves over the convecting mantle, forming a "grand unifying theory of geology".
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Advances in seismology, computer modeling, and mineralogy and crystallography at high temperatures and pressures give insights into the internal composition and structure of the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Seismologists can use the arrival times of seismic waves to image the interior of the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Early advances in this field showed the existence of a liquid outer core (where shear waves were not able to propagate) and a dense solid inner core.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These advances led to the development of a layered model of the Earth, with a lithosphere (including crust) on top, the mantle below (separated within itself by seismic discontinuities at 410 and 660 kilometers), and the outer core and inner core below that.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Starting in the 1970s, seismologists have been able to use new techniques such as seismic full-waveform inversion to create detailed images of wave speeds inside the earth in the same way a doctor images a body in a CT scan.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These images have led to a much more detailed view of the interior of the Earth, and have replaced the simplified layered model with a much more dynamic model.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Mineralogists have been able to use the pressure and temperature data from the seismic and modeling studies alongside knowledge of the elemental composition of the Earth to reproduce these conditions in experimental settings and measure changes within the crystal structure.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These studies explain the chemical changes associated with the major seismic discontinuities in the mantle and show the crystallographic structures expected in the inner core of the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The geological time scale encompasses the history of the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] It is bracketed at the earliest by the dates of the first Solar System material at 4.567 Ga (or 4.567 billion years ago) and the formation of the Earth at 4.54 Ga (4.54 billion years), which is the beginning of the Hadean eon – a division of geological time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] At the later end of the scale, it is marked by the present day (in the Holocene epoch).
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The following five timelines show the geologic time scale to scale.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The first shows the entire time from the formation of Earth to the present, but this gives little space for the most recent eon.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The second timeline shows an expanded view of the most recent eon.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In a similar way, the most recent era is expanded in the third timeline, the most recent period is expanded in the fourth timeline, and the most recent epoch is expanded in the fifth timeline.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The epochs of lunar history are based on the chronology of impact events, and they are named after defining major impacts.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Hence, the Imbrian is named after the formation of the Mare Imbrium basin.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The ages of older lunar basins can be dated based on the strength of their intrinsic magnetic field, since the early Moon had a magnetic field that faded over time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The ages of craters can be estimated by morphological and stratigraphic classifications, with younger craters overlapping older impacts and generally showing less impact wear.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Methods for relative dating were developed when geology first emerged as a natural science.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geologists still use the following principles today as a means to provide information about geological history and the timing of geological events.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The *principle of uniformitarianism* states that the geological processes observed in operation that modify the Earth's crust at present have worked in much the same way over geological time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The *principle of intrusive relationships* concerns crosscutting intrusions.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In geology, when an igneous intrusion cuts across a formation of sedimentary rock, it can be determined that the igneous intrusion is younger than the sedimentary rock.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Different types of intrusions include stocks, laccoliths, batholiths, sills and dikes.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The *principle of cross-cutting relationships* pertains to the formation of faults and the age of the sequences through which they cut.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Faults are younger than the rocks they cut; accordingly, if a fault is found that penetrates some formations but not those on top of it, then the formations that were cut are older than the fault, and the ones that are not cut must be younger than the fault.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Finding the key bed in these situations may help determine whether the fault is a normal fault or a thrust fault.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The *principle of inclusions and components* states that, with sedimentary rocks, if inclusions (or *clasts*) are found in a formation, then the inclusions must be older than the formation that contains them.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] For example, in sedimentary rocks, it is common for gravel from an older formation to be ripped up and included in a newer layer.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] A similar situation with igneous rocks occurs when xenoliths are found.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These foreign bodies are picked up as magma or lava flows, and are incorporated, later to cool in the matrix.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] As a result, xenoliths are older than the rock that contains them.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The *principle of original horizontality* states that the deposition of sediments occurs as essentially horizontal beds.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Observation of modern marine and non-marine sediments in a wide variety of environments supports this generalization (although cross-bedding is inclined, the overall orientation of cross-bedded units is horizontal).
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The *principle of superposition* states that a sedimentary rock layer in a tectonically undisturbed sequence is younger than the one beneath it and older than the one above it.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Logically a younger layer cannot slip beneath a layer previously deposited.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This principle allows sedimentary layers to be viewed as a form of the vertical timeline, a partial or complete record of the time elapsed from deposition of the lowest layer to deposition of the highest bed.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The *principle of faunal succession* is based on the appearance of fossils in sedimentary rocks.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] As organisms exist during the same period throughout the world, their presence or (sometimes) absence provides a relative age of the formations where they appear.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Based on principles that William Smith laid out almost a hundred years before the publication of Charles Darwin's theory of evolution, the principles of succession developed independently of evolutionary thought.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The principle becomes quite complex, however, given the uncertainties of fossilization, localization of fossil types due to lateral changes in habitat (facies change in sedimentary strata), and that not all fossils formed globally at the same time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geologists use methods to determine the absolute age of rock samples and geological events.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These may be used in conjunction with relative dating methods or to calibrate relative methods.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] At the beginning of the 20th century, advancement in geological science was facilitated by the ability to obtain accurate absolute dates to geological events using radioactive isotopes and other methods.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This changed the understanding of geological time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Previously, geologists could only use fossils and stratigraphic correlation to date sections of rock relative to one another.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] With isotopic dates, it became possible to assign absolute ages to rock units, and these absolute dates could be applied to fossil sequences in which there was datable material, converting the old relative ages into new absolute ages.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These are used in geochronologic and thermochronologic studies.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The most suitable isotope systems for this purpose include uranium–lead, rubidium–strontium, and potassium–argon.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Uranium–thorium dating is used for dating calcium-carbonate.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Dating of lava and volcanic ash layers found within a stratigraphic sequence can provide absolute age data for sedimentary rock units that do not contain radioactive isotopes and calibrate relative dating techniques.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These methods can be used to determine ages of pluton emplacement.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Fractionation of the lanthanide series elements is used to compute ages since rocks were removed from the mantle.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Other methods are used for more recent events.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Optically stimulated luminescence and cosmogenic radionuclide dating are used to date surfaces and/or erosion rates.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Dendrochronology can be used for the dating of landscapes.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Radiocarbon dating is used for geologically young materials containing organic carbon.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Thermochemical techniques can be used to determine temperature profiles within the crust, the uplift of mountain ranges, and paleo-topography.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The geology of an area changes through time as rock units are deposited and inserted, and deformational processes alter their shapes and locations.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Rock units are first emplaced either by deposition onto the surface or intrusion into the overlying rock.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Deposition can occur when sediments settle onto the surface of the Earth and later lithify into sedimentary rock, or when as volcanic material such as volcanic ash or lava flows blanket the surface.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Igneous intrusions such as batholiths, laccoliths, dikes, and sills, push upwards into the overlying rock, and crystallize as they intrude.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] After the initial sequence of rocks has been deposited, the rock units can be deformed and/or metamorphosed.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Deformation typically occurs as a result of horizontal shortening, horizontal extension, or side-to-side (strike-slip) motion.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These structural regimes broadly relate to convergent boundaries, divergent boundaries, and transform boundaries, respectively, between tectonic plates.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] When rock units are placed under horizontal compression, they shorten and become thicker.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Because rock units, other than muds, do not significantly change in volume, this is accomplished in two primary ways: through faulting and folding.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In the shallow crust, where brittle deformation can occur, thrust faults form, which causes the deeper rock to move on top of the shallower rock.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Because deeper rock is often older, as noted by the principle of superposition, this can result in older rocks moving on top of younger ones.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Movement along faults can result in folding, either because the faults are not planar or because rock layers are dragged along, forming drag folds as slip occurs along the fault.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Deeper in the Earth, rocks behave plastically and fold instead of faulting.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These folds can either be those where the material in the center of the fold buckles upwards, creating "antiforms", or where it buckles downwards, creating "synforms".
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] If the tops of the rock units within the folds remain pointing upwards, they are called anticlines and synclines, respectively.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] If some of the units in the fold are facing downward, the structure is called an overturned anticline or syncline, and if all of the rock units are overturned or the correct up-direction is unknown, they are simply called by the most general terms, antiforms, and synforms.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Even higher pressures and temperatures during horizontal shortening can cause both folding and metamorphism of the rocks.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This metamorphism causes changes in the mineral composition of the rocks; creates a foliation, or planar surface, that is related to mineral growth under stress.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This can remove signs of the original textures of the rocks, such as bedding in sedimentary rocks, flow features of lavas, and crystal patterns in crystalline rocks.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Extension causes the rock units as a whole to become longer and thinner.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This is primarily accomplished through normal faulting and through the ductile stretching and thinning.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Normal faults drop rock units that are higher below those that are lower.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This typically results in younger units ending up below older units.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Stretching of units can result in their thinning.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In fact, at one location within the Maria Fold and Thrust Belt, the entire sedimentary sequence of the Grand Canyon appears over a length of less than a meter.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Rocks at the depth to be ductilely stretched are often metamorphosed.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These stretched rocks can pinch into lenses, known as *boudins*, after the French word for "sausage" because of their visual similarity.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Where rock units slide past one another, strike-slip faults develop in shallow regions, and become shear zones at deeper depths where the rocks deform ductilely.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The addition of new rock units, both depositionally and intrusively, often occurs during deformation.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Faulting and other deformational processes result in the creation of topographic gradients, causing material on the rock unit that is increasing in elevation to be eroded by hillslopes and channels.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These sediments are deposited on the rock unit that is going down.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Continual motion along the fault maintains the topographic gradient in spite of the movement of sediment and continues to create accommodation space for the material to deposit.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Deformational events are often associated with volcanism and igneous activity.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Volcanic ashes and lavas accumulate on the surface, and igneous intrusions enter from below.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Dikes, long, planar igneous intrusions, enter along cracks, and therefore often form in large numbers in areas that are being actively deformed.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This can result in the emplacement of dike swarms, such as those that are observable across the Canadian shield, or rings of dikes around the lava tube of a volcano.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] All of these processes do not necessarily occur in a single environment and do not necessarily occur in a single order.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The Hawaiian Islands, for example, consist almost entirely of layered basaltic lava flows.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The sedimentary sequences of the mid-continental United States and the Grand Canyon in the southwestern United States contain almost-undeformed stacks of sedimentary rocks that have remained in place since Cambrian time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Other areas are much more geologically complex.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In the southwestern United States, sedimentary, volcanic, and intrusive rocks have been metamorphosed, faulted, foliated, and folded.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Even older rocks, such as the Acasta gneiss of the Slave craton in northwestern Canada, the oldest known rock in the world have been metamorphosed to the point where their origin is indiscernible without laboratory analysis.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In many places, the Grand Canyon in the southwestern United States being a very visible example, the lower rock units were metamorphosed and deformed, and then deformation ended and the upper, undeformed units were deposited.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Although any amount of rock emplacement and rock deformation can occur, and they can occur any number of times, these concepts provide a guide to understanding the geological history of an area.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geologists use a number of fields, laboratory, and numerical modeling methods to decipher Earth history and to understand the processes that occur on and inside the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In typical geological investigations, geologists use primary information related to petrology (the study of rocks), stratigraphy (the study of sedimentary layers), and structural geology (the study of positions of rock units and their deformation).
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In many cases, geologists study modern soils, rivers, landscapes, and glaciers; investigate past and current life and biogeochemical pathways, and use geophysical methods to investigate the subsurface.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Sub-specialities of geology may distinguish *endogenous* and *exogenous* geology.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geological field work varies depending on the task at hand.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] , thin sections are used to study rocks.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The method is based on the distinct refractive indexes of different minerals.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In addition to identifying rocks in the field (lithology), petrologists identify rock samples in the laboratory.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Two of the primary methods for identifying rocks in the laboratory are through optical microscopy (such as with the petrographic microscope) and by using an electron microprobe.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In the electron microprobe, individual locations are analyzed for their exact chemical compositions and variation in composition within individual crystals.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Stable and radioactive isotope studies provide insight into the geochemical evolution of rock units.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Petrologists can use fluid inclusion data and perform high temperature and pressure physical experiments to understand the temperatures and pressures at which different mineral phases appear, and how they change through igneous and metamorphic processes.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This research can be extrapolated to the field to understand metamorphic processes and the conditions of crystallization of igneous rocks.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This work can help to explain processes that occur within the Earth, such as subduction and magma chamber evolution.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Structural geologists use microscopic analysis of oriented thin sections of geological samples to observe the fabric within the rocks, which gives information about strain within the crystalline structure of the rocks.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] They plot and combine measurements of geological structures to better understand the orientations of faults and folds to reconstruct the history of rock deformation in the area.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In addition, they perform analog and numerical experiments of rock deformation in large and small settings.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The analysis of structures is often accomplished by plotting the orientations of various features onto stereonets.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] A stereonet is a stereographic projection of a sphere onto a plane, in which planes are projected as lines and lines are projected as points.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These can be used to find the locations of fold axes, relationships between faults, and relationships between other geological structures.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Among the most well-known experiments in structural geology are those involving orogenic wedges, which are zones in which mountains are built along convergent tectonic plate boundaries.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In the analog versions of these experiments, horizontal layers of sand are pulled along a lower surface into a back stop, which results in realistic-looking patterns of faulting and the growth of a critically tapered (all angles remain the same) orogenic wedge.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Numerical models work in the same way as these analog models, though they are often more sophisticated and can include patterns of erosion and uplift in the mountain belt.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This helps to show the relationship between erosion and the shape of a mountain range.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These studies can give useful information about pathways for metamorphism through pressure, temperature, space, and time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In the laboratory, stratigraphers analyze samples of stratigraphic sections that can be returned from the field, such as those from drill cores.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Stratigraphers analyze data from geophysical surveys that show the locations of stratigraphic units in the subsurface.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geophysical data and well logs can be combined to produce a better view of the subsurface, and stratigraphers often use computer programs to do this in three dimensions.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Stratigraphers can then use these data to reconstruct ancient processes occurring on the surface of the Earth, interpret past environments, and locate areas for water, coal, and hydrocarbon extraction.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In the laboratory, biostratigraphers analyze rock samples from outcrop and drill cores for the fossils found in them.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These fossils help scientists to date the core and to understand the depositional environment in which the rock units formed.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geochronologists precisely date rocks within the stratigraphic section to provide better absolute bounds on the timing and rates of deposition.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Magnetic stratigraphers look for signs of magnetic reversals in igneous rock units within the drill cores.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Other scientists perform stable-isotope studies on the rocks to gain information about past climate.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] With the advent of space exploration in the twentieth century, geologists have begun to look at other planetary bodies in the same ways that have been developed to study the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This new field of study is called planetary geology (sometimes known as astrogeology) and relies on known geological principles to study other bodies of the Solar System.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This is a major aspect of planetary science, and largely focuses on the terrestrial planets, icy moons, asteroids, comets, and meteorites.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] However, some planetary geophysicists study the giant planets and exoplanets.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Although the Greek-language-origin prefix *geo* refers to Earth, "geology" is often used in conjunction with the names of other planetary bodies when describing their composition and internal processes: examples are "the geology of Mars" and "Lunar geology".
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Specialized terms such as *selenology* (studies of the Moon), *areology* (of Mars), *hermesology* (of Mercury), etc., are also in use.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Although planetary geologists are interested in studying all aspects of other planets, a significant focus is to search for evidence of past or present life on other worlds.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This has led to many missions whose primary or ancillary purpose is to examine planetary bodies for evidence of life.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] One of these is the Phoenix lander, which analyzed Martian polar soil for water, chemical, and mineralogical constituents related to biological processes.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Economic geology is a branch of geology that deals with aspects of economic minerals that humankind uses to fulfill various needs.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Economic minerals are those extracted profitably for various practical uses.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Economic geologists help locate and manage the Earth's natural resources, such as petroleum and coal, as well as mineral resources, which include metals such as iron, copper, and uranium.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Mining geology consists of the extractions of mineral and ore resources from the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Some resources of economic interests include gemstones, metals such as gold and copper, and many industrial minerals such as asbestos, magnesite, perlite, mica, phosphates, zeolites, clay, silica, and pumice, as well as elements such as sulfur and helium.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Petroleum geologists study the locations of the subsurface of the Earth that can contain extractable hydrocarbons, especially petroleum and natural gas.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Because many of these reservoirs are found in sedimentary basins, they study the formation of these basins, their sedimentary and tectonic evolution, and the present-day positions of the rock units.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Engineering geology is the application of geological principles to engineering practice for the purpose of assuring that the geological factors affecting the location, design, construction, operation, and maintenance of engineering works are properly addressed.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Engineering geology is distinct from geological engineering, particularly in North America.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In the field of civil engineering, geological principles and analyses are used in order to ascertain the mechanical principles of the material on which structures are built.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This allows tunnels to be built without collapsing, bridges and skyscrapers to be built with sturdy foundations, and buildings to be built that will not settle in clay and mud.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geology and geological principles can be applied to various environmental problems such as stream restoration, the restoration of brownfields, and the understanding of the interaction between natural habitat and the geological environment.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Groundwater hydrology, or hydrogeology, is used to locate groundwater, which can often provide a ready supply of uncontaminated water and is especially important in arid regions, and to monitor the spread of contaminants in groundwater wells.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geologists obtain data through stratigraphy, boreholes, core samples, and ice cores.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Ice cores and sediment cores are used for paleoclimate reconstructions, which tell geologists about past and present temperature, precipitation, and sea level across the globe.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] These datasets are our primary source of information on global climate change outside of instrumental data.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Geologists and geophysicists study natural hazards in order to enact safe building codes and warning systems that are used to prevent loss of property and life.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The study of the physical material of the Earth dates back at least to ancient Greece when Theophrastus (372–287 BCE) wrote the work *Peri Lithon* (*On Stones*).
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] During the Roman period, Pliny the Elder wrote in detail of the many minerals and metals, then in practical use – even correctly noting the origin of amber.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Additionally, in the 4th century BCE Aristotle made critical observations of the slow rate of geological change.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] He observed the composition of the land and formulated a theory where the Earth changes at a slow rate and that these changes cannot be observed during one person's lifetime.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Aristotle developed one of the first evidence-based concepts connected to the geological realm regarding the rate at which the Earth physically changes.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Abu al-Rayhan al-Biruni (973–1048 CE) was one of the earliest Persian geologists, whose works included the earliest writings on the geology of India, hypothesizing that the Indian subcontinent was once a sea.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Georgius Agricola (1494–1555) published his groundbreaking work *De Natura Fossilium* in 1546 and is seen as the founder of geology as a scientific discipline.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Nicolas Steno (1638–1686) is credited with the law of superposition, the principle of original horizontality, and the principle of lateral continuity: three defining principles of stratigraphy.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The word *geology* was first used by Ulisse Aldrovandi in 1603, then by Jean-André Deluc in 1778 and introduced as a fixed term by Horace-Bénédict de Saussure in 1779.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The word is derived from the Greek γῆ, *gê*, meaning "earth" and λόγος, *logos*, meaning "speech".
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] But according to another source, the word "geology" comes from a Norwegian, Mikkel Pedersøn Escholt (1600–1669), who was a priest and scholar.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Escholt first used the definition in his book titled, *Geologia Norvegica* (1657).
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] William Smith (1769–1839) drew some of the first geological maps and began the process of ordering rock strata (layers) by examining the fossils contained in them.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In 1763, Mikhail Lomonosov published his treatise *On the Strata of Earth*.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] His work was the first narrative of modern geology, based on the unity of processes in time and explanation of the Earth's past from the present.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] James Hutton (1726–1797) is often viewed as the first modern geologist.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In 1785 he presented a paper entitled *Theory of the Earth* to the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In his paper, he explained his theory that the Earth must be much older than had previously been supposed to allow enough time for mountains to be eroded and for sediments to form new rocks at the bottom of the sea, which in turn were raised up to become dry land.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Hutton published a two-volume version of his ideas in 1795.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The first geological map of the U.S. was produced in 1809 by William Maclure.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In 1807, Maclure commenced the self-imposed task of making a geological survey of the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Almost every state in the Union was traversed and mapped by him, the Allegheny Mountains being crossed and recrossed some 50 times.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The results of his unaided labours were submitted to the American Philosophical Society in a memoir entitled *Observations on the Geology of the United States explanatory of a Geological Map*, and published in the *Society's Transactions*, together with the nation's first geological map.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This antedates William Smith's geological map of England by six years, although it was constructed using a different classification of rocks.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Sir Charles Lyell (1797–1875) first published his famous book, *Principles of Geology*, in 1830.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This book, which influenced the thought of Charles Darwin, successfully promoted the doctrine of uniformitarianism.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] This theory states that slow geological processes have occurred throughout the Earth's history and are still occurring today.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] In contrast, catastrophism is the theory that Earth's features formed in single, catastrophic events and remained unchanged thereafter.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Though Hutton believed in uniformitarianism, the idea was not widely accepted at the time.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Much of 19th-century geology revolved around the question of the Earth's exact age.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Estimates varied from a few hundred thousand to billions of years.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] By the early 20th century, radiometric dating allowed the Earth's age to be estimated at two billion years.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The awareness of this vast amount of time opened the door to new theories about the processes that shaped the planet.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Some of the most significant advances in 20th-century geology have been the development of the theory of plate tectonics in the 1960s and the refinement of estimates of the planet's age.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Plate tectonics theory arose from two separate geological observations: seafloor spreading and continental drift.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] The theory revolutionized the Earth sciences.
[src:albert-w-bally/geology] Today the Earth is known to be approximately 4.5 billion years old.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] It is one of the oldest sciences, dating back to antiquity with the development of early seismometers and magnetic compasses, and later extending to Newtonian analyses of tides, precession, and Earth’s physical properties.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Geophysics integrates theory, observation, and experiment to investigate Earth and planetary systems across diverse spatial and temporal scales.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Its methods include field measurements, laboratory experiments, remote sensing, numerical modelling, and data analysis of both natural and instrumented records, including signal processing.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] As a unifying physical framework for Earth and planetary studies, geophysics connects phenomena from the deep interior to the upper atmosphere and near-space environment, providing the basis for understanding of planetary evolution, dynamics, and habitability.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Geophysics is a highly interdisciplinary subject, and geophysicists contribute to every area of the Earth sciences, while some geophysicists conduct research in the planetary sciences.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] To provide a more clear idea on what constitutes geophysics, this section describes phenomena that are studied in physics and how they relate to the Earth and its surroundings.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Geophysicists also investigate the physical processes and properties of the Earth, its fluid layers, and magnetic field along with the near-Earth environment in the Solar System, which includes other planetary bodies.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The gravitational pull of the Moon and Sun gives rise to two high tides and two low tides every lunar day, or every 24 hours and 50 minutes.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Therefore, there is a gap of 12 hours and 25 minutes between every high tide and between every low tide.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Gravitational forces make rocks press down on deeper rocks, increasing their density as the depth increases.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Measurements of gravitational acceleration and gravitational potential at the Earth's surface and above it can be used to look for mineral deposits (see gravity anomaly and gravimetry).
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The surface gravitational field provides information on the dynamics of tectonic plates.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The geopotential surface called the geoid is one definition of the shape of the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The geoid would be the global mean sea level if the oceans were in equilibrium and could be extended through the continents (such as with very narrow canals).
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Seismic waves are vibrations that travel through the Earth's interior or along its surface.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The entire Earth can also oscillate in forms that are called normal modes or free oscillations of the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Ground motions from waves or normal modes are measured using seismographs.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] If the waves come from a localized source such as an earthquake or explosion, measurements at more than one location can be used to locate the source.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The locations of earthquakes provide information on plate tectonics and mantle convection.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Recording of seismic waves from controlled sources provides information on the region that the waves travel through.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] If the density or composition of the rock changes, waves are reflected.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Reflections recorded using Reflection Seismology can provide a wealth of information on the structure of the earth up to several kilometers deep and are used to increase our understanding of the geology as well as to explore for oil and gas.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Changes in the travel direction, called refraction, can be used to infer the deep structure of the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Understanding their mechanisms, which depend on the type of earthquake (e.g., intraplate or deep focus), can lead to better estimates of earthquake risk and improvements in earthquake engineering.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] There is always a downward electric field near the surface that averages 120 volts per meter.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The galactic cosmic rays penetrating the atmosphere result in its ionization relative to the solid Earth, leaving it with a net positive charge.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] A current of about 1800 amperes flows in the global circuit.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] It flows downward from the ionosphere over most of the Earth and back upwards through thunderstorms.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The flow is manifested by lightning below the clouds and sprites above.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] A variety of electric methods are used in geophysical survey.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Some measure spontaneous potential, a potential that arises in the ground because of human-made or natural disturbances.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Telluric currents flow in Earth and the oceans.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] They have two causes: electromagnetic induction by the time-varying, external-origin geomagnetic field and motion of conducting bodies (such as seawater) across the Earth's permanent magnetic field.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The distribution of telluric current density can be used to detect variations in electrical resistivity of underground structures.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Geophysicists can also provide the electric current themselves (see induced polarization and electrical resistivity tomography).
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Electromagnetic waves occur in the ionosphere and magnetosphere as well as in Earth's outer core.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Dawn chorus is believed to be caused by high-energy electrons that get caught in the Van Allen radiation belt.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Whistlers are produced by lightning strikes.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Electromagnetic waves may also be generated by earthquakes (see seismo-electromagnetics).
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In the highly conductive liquid iron of the outer core, magnetic fields are generated by electric currents through electromagnetic induction.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Alfvén waves are magnetohydrodynamic waves in the magnetosphere or the Earth's core.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In the core, they probably have little observable effect on the Earth's magnetic field, but slower waves such as magnetic Rossby waves may be one source of geomagnetic secular variation.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Electromagnetic methods that are used for geophysical survey include transient electromagnetics, magnetotellurics, surface nuclear magnetic resonance and electromagnetic seabed logging.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The Earth's magnetic field protects the Earth from the deadly solar wind and has long been used for navigation.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] It originates in the fluid motions of the outer core.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The magnetic field in the upper atmosphere gives rise to the auroras.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The Earth's field is roughly like a tilted dipole, but it changes over time (a phenomenon called geomagnetic secular variation).
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Mostly the geomagnetic pole stays near the geographic pole, but at random intervals averaging 440,000 to a million years or so, the polarity of the Earth's field reverses.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Geologists observed geomagnetic reversal recorded in volcanic rocks, through magnetostratigraphy correlation (see natural remanent magnetization) and their signature can be seen as parallel linear magnetic anomaly stripes on the seafloor.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] These stripes provide quantitative information on seafloor spreading, a part of plate tectonics.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] They are the basis of magnetostratigraphy, which correlates magnetic reversals with other stratigraphies to construct geologic time scales.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In addition, the magnetization in rocks can be used to measure the motion of continents.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Radioactive decay accounts for about 80% of the Earth's internal heat, powering the geodynamo and plate tectonics.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The main heat-producing isotopes are potassium-40, uranium-238, uranium-235, and thorium-232.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Radioactive elements are used for radiometric dating, the primary method for establishing an absolute time scale in geochronology.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Unstable isotopes decay at predictable rates, and the decay rates of different isotopes cover several orders of magnitude, so radioactive decay can be used to accurately date both recent events and events in past geologic eras.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Radiometric mapping using ground and airborne gamma spectrometry can be used to map the concentration and distribution of radioisotopes near the Earth's surface, which is useful for mapping lithology and alteration.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Fluid motions occur in the magnetosphere, atmosphere, ocean, mantle and core.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Even the mantle, though it has an enormous viscosity, flows like a fluid over long time intervals.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] This flow is reflected in phenomena such as isostasy, post-glacial rebound and mantle plumes.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The mantle flow drives plate tectonics and the flow in the Earth's core drives the geodynamo.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Geophysical fluid dynamics is a primary tool in physical oceanography and meteorology.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The rotation of the Earth has profound effects on the Earth's fluid dynamics, often due to the Coriolis effect.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In the atmosphere, it gives rise to large-scale patterns like Rossby waves and determines the basic circulation patterns of storms.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In the ocean, they drive large-scale circulation patterns as well as Kelvin waves and Ekman spirals at the ocean surface.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In the Earth's core, the circulation of the molten iron is structured by Taylor columns.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Waves and other phenomena in the magnetosphere can be modeled using magnetohydrodynamics.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The Earth is cooling, and the resulting heat flow generates the Earth's magnetic field through the geodynamo and plate tectonics through mantle convection.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The main sources of heat are: primordial heat due to Earth's cooling and radioactivity in the planets upper crust.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] There is also some contributions from phase transitions.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Heat is mostly carried to the surface by thermal convection, although there are two thermal boundary layers – the core–mantle boundary and the lithosphere – in which heat is transported by conduction.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Some heat is carried up from the bottom of the mantle by mantle plumes.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The heat flow at the Earth's surface is about 4.2 × 1013 W, and it is a potential source of geothermal energy.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The physical properties of minerals must be understood to infer the composition of the Earth's interior from seismology, the geothermal gradient and other sources of information.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Mineral physicists study the elastic properties of minerals; their high-pressure phase diagrams, melting points and equations of state at high pressure; and the rheological properties of rocks, or their ability to flow.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Deformation of rocks by creep make flow possible, although over short times the rocks are brittle.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The viscosity of rocks is affected by temperature and pressure, and in turn, determines the rates at which tectonic plates move.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Water is a very complex substance and its unique properties are essential for life.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Its physical properties shape the hydrosphere and are an essential part of the water cycle and climate.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Its thermodynamic properties determine evaporation and the thermal gradient in the atmosphere.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The many types of precipitation involve a complex mixture of processes such as coalescence, supercooling and supersaturation.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Some precipitated water becomes groundwater, and groundwater flow includes phenomena such as percolation, while the conductivity of water makes electrical and electromagnetic methods useful for tracking groundwater flow.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Physical properties of water such as salinity have a large effect on its motion in the oceans.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The many phases of ice form the cryosphere and come in forms like ice sheets, glaciers, sea ice, freshwater ice, snow, and frozen ground (or permafrost).
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Contrary to popular belief, the earth is not entirely spherical but instead generally exhibits an ellipsoid shape- which is a result of the centrifugal forces the planet generates due to its constant motion.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] These forces cause the planets diameter to bulge towards the Equator and results in the ellipsoid shape.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Evidence from seismology, heat flow at the surface, and mineral physics is combined with the Earth's mass and moment of inertia to infer the composition, density, temperature, and pressure of the Earth's interior.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] For example, the Earth's mean specific gravity (5.515) is far higher than the typical specific gravity of rocks at the surface (2.7–3.3), implying that the deeper material is denser.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] This is also implied by its low moment of inertia ( 0.33 *M R*2, compared to 0.4 *M R*2 for a sphere of constant density).
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] However, some of the density increase is compression under the enormous pressures inside the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The effect of pressure can be calculated using the Adams–Williamson equation.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The conclusion is that pressure alone cannot account for the increase in density.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Instead, we know that the Earth's core is composed of an alloy of iron and other minerals.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Reconstructions of seismic waves in the deep interior of the Earth show that there are no S-waves in the outer core.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] This indicates that the outer core is liquid, because liquids cannot support shear.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The outer core is liquid, and the motion of this highly conductive fluid generates the Earth's field.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Earth's inner core, however, is solid because of the enormous pressure.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Reconstruction of seismic reflections in the deep interior indicates some major discontinuities in seismic velocities that demarcate the major zones of the Earth: inner core, outer core, mantle, lithosphere and crust.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The mantle itself is divided into the upper mantle, transition zone, lower mantle and *D′′* layer.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Between the crust and the mantle is the Mohorovičić discontinuity.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The seismic model of the Earth does not by itself determine the composition of the layers.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] For a complete model of the Earth, mineral physics is needed to interpret seismic velocities in terms of composition.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The mineral properties are temperature-dependent, so the geotherm must also be determined.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] This requires physical theory for thermal conduction and convection and the heat contribution of radioactive elements.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The main model for the radial structure of the interior of the Earth is the preliminary reference Earth model (PREM).
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Some parts of this model have been updated by recent findings in mineral physics (see post-perovskite) and supplemented by seismic tomography.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The mantle is mainly composed of silicates, and the boundaries between layers of the mantle are consistent with phase transitions.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The mantle acts as a solid for seismic waves, but under high pressures and temperatures, it deforms so that over millions of years it acts like a liquid.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] If a planet's magnetic field is strong enough, its interaction with the solar wind forms a magnetosphere.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Early space probes mapped out the gross dimensions of the Earth's magnetic field, which extends about 10 Earth radii towards the Sun.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The solar wind, a stream of charged particles, streams out and around the terrestrial magnetic field, and continues behind the magnetic tail, hundreds of Earth radii downstream.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Inside the magnetosphere, there are relatively dense regions of solar wind particles called the Van Allen radiation belts.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Geophysical measurements are generally at a particular time and place.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Accurate measurements of position, along with earth deformation and gravity, are the province of geodesy.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] While geodesy and geophysics are separate fields, the two are so closely connected that many scientific organizations such as the American Geophysical Union, the Canadian Geophysical Union and the International Union of Geodesy and Geophysics encompass both.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Absolute positions are most frequently determined using the global positioning system (GPS).
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] A three-dimensional position is calculated using messages from four or more visible satellites and referred to the 1980 Geodetic Reference System.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] An alternative, optical astronomy, combines astronomical coordinates and the local gravity vector to get geodetic coordinates.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] This method only provides the position in two coordinates and is more difficult to use than GPS.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] However, it is useful for measuring motions of the Earth such as nutation and Chandler wobble.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Relative positions of two or more points can be determined using very-long-baseline interferometry.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Gravity measurements became part of geodesy because they were needed to related measurements at the surface of the Earth to the reference coordinate system.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Gravity measurements on land can be made using gravimeters deployed either on the surface or in helicopter flyovers.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Since the 1960s, the Earth's gravity field has been measured by analyzing the motion of satellites.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Sea level can also be measured by satellites using radar altimetry, contributing to a more accurate geoid.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In 2002, NASA launched the Gravity Recovery and Climate Experiment (GRACE), wherein two twin satellites map variations in Earth's gravity field by making measurements of the distance between the two satellites using GPS and a microwave ranging system.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Gravity variations detected by GRACE include those caused by changes in ocean currents; runoff and ground water depletion; melting ice sheets and glaciers.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Satellites in space have made it possible to collect data from not only the visible light region, but in other areas of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The planets can be characterized by their force fields: gravity and their magnetic fields, which are studied through geophysics and space physics.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Measuring the changes in acceleration experienced by spacecraft as they orbit has allowed fine details of the gravity fields of the planets to be mapped.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] For example, in the 1970s, the gravity field disturbances above lunar maria were measured through lunar orbiters, which led to the discovery of concentrations of mass, mascons, beneath the Imbrium, Serenitatis, Crisium, Nectaris and Humorum basins.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Since geophysics is concerned with the shape of the Earth, and by extension the mapping of features around and in the planet, geophysical measurements include high accuracy GPS measurements.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] These measurements are processed to increase their accuracy through differential GPS processing.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Once the geophysical measurements have been processed and inverted, the interpreted results are plotted using GIS.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Programs such as ArcGIS and Geosoft were built to meet these needs and include many geophysical functions that are built-in, such as upward continuation, and the calculation of the measurement derivative such as the first-vertical derivative.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Many geophysics companies have designed in-house geophysics programs that pre-date ArcGIS and GeoSoft in order to meet the visualization requirements of a geophysical dataset.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Exploration geophysics is a branch of applied geophysics that involves the development and utilization of different seismic or electromagnetic methods which the aim of investigating different energy, mineral and water resources.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] This is done through the uses of various remote sensing platforms such as; satellites, aircraft, boats, drones, borehole sensing equipment and seismic receivers.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] These equipment are often used in conjunction with different geophysical methods such as magnetic, gravimetry, electromagnetic, radiometric, barometry methods in order to gather the data.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The remote sensing platforms used in exploration geophysics are not perfect and need adjustments done on them in order to accurately account for the effects that the platform itself may have on the collected data.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] For example, when gathering aeromagnetic data (aircraft gathered magnetic data) using a conventional fixed-wing aircraft- the platform has to be adjusted to account for the electromagnetic currents that it may generate as it passes through Earth's magnetic field.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] There are also corrections related to changes in measured potential field intensity as the Earth rotates, as the Earth orbits the Sun, and as the moon orbits the Earth.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Geophysical measurements are often recorded as time-series with GPS location.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Signal processing involves the correction of time-series data for unwanted noise or errors introduced by the measurement platform, such as aircraft vibrations in gravity data.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] It also involves the reduction of sources of noise, such as diurnal corrections in magnetic data.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Geophysics emerged as a separate discipline only in the 19th century, from the intersection of physical geography, geology, astronomy, meteorology, and physics.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The first known use of the word *geophysics* was in German ("Geophysik") by Julius Fröbel in 1834.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] However, many geophysical phenomena – such as the Earth's magnetic field and earthquakes – have been investigated since the ancient era.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The magnetic compass existed in China back as far as the fourth century BC.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] It was used as much for feng shui as for navigation on land.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] It was not until good steel needles could be forged that compasses were used for navigation at sea; before that, they could not retain their magnetism long enough to be useful.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The first mention of a compass in Europe was in 1190 AD.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In circa 240 BC, Eratosthenes of Cyrene deduced that the Earth was round and measured the circumference of Earth with great precision.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] He developed a system of latitude and longitude.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Perhaps the earliest contribution to seismology was the invention of a seismoscope by the prolific inventor Zhang Heng in 132 AD.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] This instrument was designed to drop a bronze ball from the mouth of a dragon into the mouth of a toad.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] By looking at which of eight toads had the ball, one could determine the direction of the earthquake.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] It was 1571 years before the first design for a seismoscope was published in Europe, by Jean de la Hautefeuille.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The 17th century had major milestones that marked the beginning of modern science.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In 1600, William Gilbert release a publication titled *De Magnete* (1600) where he conducted series of experiments on both natural magnets (called 'loadstones') and artificially magnetized iron.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] His experiments lead to observations involving a small compass needle (versorium) which replicated magnetic behaviours when subjected to a spherical magnet, along with it experiencing 'magnetic dips' when it was pivoted on a horizontal axis.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] HIs findings led to the deduction that compasses point north due to the Earth itself being a giant magnet.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In 1687 Isaac Newton published his work titled *Principia* which was pivotal in the development of modern scientific fields such as astronomy and physics.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] In it, Newton both laid the foundations for classical mechanics and gravitation, as well as explained different geophysical phenomena such as the precession of the equinox (the orbit of whole star patterns along an ecliptic axis.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] Newton's theory of gravity had gained so much success, that it resulted in changing the main objective of physics in that era to unravel natures fundamental forces, and their characterizations in laws.
[src:albert-w-bally/geophysics] The first seismometer, an instrument capable of keeping a continuous record of seismic activity, was built by James Forbes in 1844.
[src:albert-w-bally/gustav-steinmann-medal] The **Gustav-Steinmann-Medaille** is a scientific award by the Deutsche Geologische Gesellschaft - Geologische Vereinigung (German Geological Society-Geological Association) to an individual who has made outstanding contributions in the fields of geology and earth sciences.
[src:albert-w-bally/gustav-steinmann-medal] The award is named after the German geologist and paleontologist Gustav Steinmann.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston was founded by land investors on August 30, 1836, at the confluence of Buffalo Bayou and White Oak Bayou (a point now known as Allen's Landing) and incorporated as a city on June 5, 1837.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The city is named after former General Sam Houston, who was president of the Republic of Texas and had won Texas's independence from Mexico at the Battle of San Jacinto 25 miles (40 km) east of Allen's Landing.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] After briefly serving as the capital of the Texas Republic in the late 1830s, Houston grew steadily into a regional trading center for the remainder of the 19th century.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In the mid-20th century, Houston's economy diversified, as it became home to the Texas Medical Center—the world's largest concentration of healthcare and research institutions—and NASA's Johnson Space Center, home to the Mission Control Center.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Since the late 19th century, Houston's economy has had a broad industrial base in energy, manufacturing, aeronautics, and transportation.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Leading in healthcare sectors and building oilfield equipment, Houston has the second-most *Fortune* 500 headquarters of any U.S. municipality within its city limits.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Port of Houston ranks first in the United States in international waterborne tonnage handled and second in total cargo tonnage handled.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Nicknamed the "Bayou City", "Space City", "H-Town", and "the 713", Houston has become a global city, with strengths in culture, medicine, and research.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The city's population comprises various ethnic and religious backgrounds, as well as a large and growing international community.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston is the most diverse metropolitan area in Texas and has been described as the most racially and ethnically diverse major city in the U.S.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] It is home to many cultural institutions and exhibits, such as the Houston Museum District and the Houston Theater District.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Present-day Houston sits on land that was once occupied by the Karankawa and the Atakapa indigenous peoples for at least 2,000 years before the first known settlers arrived.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] These tribes are almost nonexistent today; this was most likely caused by foreign disease, and competition with various settler groups in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] However, the land then remained largely uninhabited from the late 1700s until settlement in the 1830s.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Allen brothers—Augustus Chapman and John Kirby—explored town sites on Buffalo Bayou and Galveston Bay.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] According to historian David McComb, "[T]he brothers, on August 26, 1836, bought from Elizabeth E.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Parrott and widow of John Austin, the south half of the lower league [2,214-acre (896 ha) tract] granted to her by her late husband.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Allen brothers ran their first advertisement for Houston just four days later in the *Telegraph and Texas Register*, naming the notional town in honor of Sam Houston, who would become President later that year.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] They successfully lobbied the Republic of Texas Congress to designate Houston as the temporary capital, agreeing to provide the new government with a state capitol building.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] About a dozen persons resided in the town at the beginning of 1837, but that number grew to about 1,500 by the time the Texas Congress convened in Houston for the first time that May.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Republic of Texas granted Houston incorporation on June 5, 1837, as James S.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In the same year, Houston became the county seat of Harrisburg County (now Harris County).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 1839, the Republic of Texas relocated its capital to Austin.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The town suffered another setback that year when a yellow fever epidemic claimed about one life for every eight residents, yet it persisted as a commercial center, forming a symbiosis with its Gulf Coast port, Galveston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Landlocked farmers brought their produce to Houston, using Buffalo Bayou to gain access to Galveston and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston merchants profited from selling staples to farmers and shipping the farmers' produce to Galveston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The great majority of enslaved people in Texas came with their owners from the older slave states.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Sizable numbers, however, came through the domestic slave trade.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] New Orleans was the center of this trade in the Deep South, but slave dealers were in Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Thousands of enslaved black people lived near the city before the American Civil War.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Many of them near the city worked on sugar and cotton plantations, while most of those in the city limits had domestic and artisan jobs.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 1840, the community established a chamber of commerce, in part to promote shipping and navigation at the newly created port on Buffalo Bayou.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] By 1860, Houston had emerged as a commercial and railroad hub for the export of cotton.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Railroad spurs from the Texas inland converged in Houston, where they met rail lines to the ports of Galveston and Beaumont.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Census lists 4,845 inhabitants in Houston, including 1,069 enslaved (99 % of the city's African American population).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] During the American Civil War, Houston served as a headquarters for Confederate Major General John B.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Magruder, who used the city as an organization point for the Battle of Galveston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] After the Civil War, Houston businessmen initiated efforts to widen the city's extensive system of bayous so the city could accept more commerce between Downtown and the nearby port of Galveston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] By 1890, Houston was the railroad center of Texas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 1900, after Galveston was struck by a devastating hurricane, efforts to make Houston into a viable deep-water port were accelerated.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The following year, the discovery of oil at the Spindletop oil field near Beaumont prompted the development of the Texas petroleum industry.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 1902, President Theodore Roosevelt approved a $1 million improvement project for the Houston Ship Channel.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] By 1910, the city's population had reached 78,800, almost doubling from a decade before.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] African Americans formed a large part of the city's population, numbering 23,929 people, which was nearly one-third of Houston's residents.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] President Woodrow Wilson opened the deep-water Port of Houston in 1914, seven years after digging began.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] By 1930, Houston had become Texas's most populous city and Harris County the most populous county.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Census Bureau reported Houston's population as 77.5% White and 22.4% black.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] When World War II started, tonnage levels at the port decreased and shipping activities were suspended; however, the war did provide economic benefits for the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Petrochemical refineries and manufacturing plants were constructed along the ship channel because of the demand for petroleum and synthetic rubber products by the defense industry during the war.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Ellington Field, initially built during World War I, was revitalized as an advanced training center for bombardiers and navigators.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Brown Shipbuilding Company was founded in 1942 to build ships for the U.S.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Due to the boom in defense jobs, thousands of new workers migrated to the city, both black, and white people competing for the higher-paying jobs.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] President Roosevelt had established a policy of nondiscrimination for defense contractors, and black people gained some opportunities, especially in shipbuilding, although not without resistance from white people and increasing social tensions that erupted into occasional violence.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Economic gains of black people who entered defense industries continued in the postwar years.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Anderson Foundation formed the Texas Medical Center.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] After the war, Houston's economy reverted to being primarily port-driven.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 1948, the city annexed several unincorporated areas, more than doubling its size.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston proper began to spread across the region.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 1950, the availability of air conditioning provided impetus for many companies to relocate to Houston, where wages were lower than those in the North; this resulted in an economic boom and produced a key shift in the city's economy toward the energy sector.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The increased production of the expanded shipbuilding industry during World War II spurred Houston's growth, as did the establishment in 1961 of NASA's "Manned Spacecraft Center" (renamed the Lyndon B.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] This was the stimulus for the development of the city's aerospace industry.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Astrodome, nicknamed the "Eighth Wonder of the World", opened in 1965 as the world's first indoor domed sports stadium.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] During the late 1970s, Houston had a population boom as people from the Rust Belt states moved to Texas in large numbers.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The new residents came for numerous employment opportunities in the petroleum industry, created as a result of the Arab oil embargo.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] With the increase in professional jobs, Houston has become a destination for many college-educated persons, most recently including African Americans in a reverse Great Migration from northern areas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Brown as the city's first African American mayor.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston has continued to grow into the 21st century, with the population increasing 15.7% from 2000 to 2022.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Oil and gas have continued to fuel Houston's economic growth, with major oil companies including Phillips 66, ConocoPhillips, Occidental Petroleum, Halliburton, and ExxonMobil having their headquarters in the Houston area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 2001, Enron Corporation, a Houston company with $100 billion in revenue, became engulfed in an accounting scandal which bankrupted the company in 2001.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Healthcare had also emerged as a major industry in Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Texas Medical Center is now the largest medical complex in the world and employs over 120,000 people.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In the first decade of the 21st century, three new sports stadiums opened downtown.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 2000, the Houston Astros opened their new baseball stadium, Daikin Park, in downtown adjacent to the old Union Station.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Houston Texans were formed in 2002 as an NFL expansion team, replacing the Houston Oilers, which had left the city in 1996.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 2003, the Toyota Center opened as the home for the Houston Rockets.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 2005, the Houston Dynamo soccer team was formed.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 2017, the Houston Astros won their first World Series.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Flooding has been a recurring problem in the Houston area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In June 2001, Tropical Storm Allison dumped up to 40 inches (1,000 mm) of rain on parts of Houston, causing what was then the worst flooding in the city's history and billions of dollars in damage, and killed 20 people in Texas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In August 2005, Houston became a shelter to more than 150,000 people from New Orleans, who evacuated from Hurricane Katrina.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] One month later, about 2.5 million Houston-area residents evacuated when Hurricane Rita approached the Gulf Coast, leaving little damage to the Houston area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] This was the largest urban evacuation in the history of the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In May 2015, seven people died after 12 inches of rain fell in 10 hours during what is known as the Memorial Day Flood.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Eight people died in April 2016 during a storm that dropped 17 inches of rain.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The worst came in late August 2017, when Hurricane Harvey stalled over southeastern Texas, much like Tropical Storm Allison did sixteen years earlier, causing severe flooding in the Houston area, with some areas receiving over 50 inches (1,300 mm) of rain.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The rainfall exceeded 50 inches in several areas locally, breaking the national record for rainfall.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The damage for the Houston area was estimated at up to $125 billion U.S. dollars, and was considered to be one of the worst natural disasters in the history of the United States, with the death toll exceeding 70 people.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston's lack of zoning laws allowed unregulated building of residential homes and other structures in flood-prone areas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] However, it also resulted in more concentrated development in already urban areas than in wetlands and suburbs.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Mayor Sylvester Turner tweeted of Hurricane Harvey that "zoning wouldn't have changed anything.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] On May 16, 2024, a strong derecho caused widespread damage across the city and surrounding metropolitan area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston is 165 miles (266 km) east of Austin, 88 miles (142 km) west of the Louisiana border, and 250 miles (400 km) south of Dallas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The city has a total area of 637.4 square miles (1,651 km2); this comprises over 599.59 square miles (1,552.9 km2) of land and 22.3 square miles (58 km2) covered by water.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Most of Houston is on the gulf coastal plain, and its vegetation is classified as Western Gulf coastal grasslands while further north, it transitions into a subtropical jungle, the Big Thicket.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Much of the city was built on forested land, marshes, or swamps, and all are still visible in surrounding areas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Flat terrain and extensive greenfield development have combined to worsen flooding.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Downtown stands about 50 feet (15 m) above sea level, and the highest point in far northwest Houston is about 150 feet (46 m) in elevation.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The city once relied on groundwater for its needs, but land subsidence forced the city to turn to ground-level water sources such as Lake Houston, Lake Conroe, and Lake Livingston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The city owns surface water rights for 1.20 billion U.S. gallons (4.5 Gl) of water a day in addition to 150 million U.S. gallons (570 Ml) a day of groundwater.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston has four major bayous passing through the city that accept water from the extensive drainage system.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The ship channel continues past Galveston and then into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston is a flat, marshy area where an extensive drainage system has been built.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The adjoining prairie land drains into the city, which is prone to flooding.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Underpinning Houston's land surface are unconsolidated clays, clay shales, and poorly cemented sands up to several miles deep.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The region's geology developed from river deposits formed from the erosion of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] These sediments consist of a series of sands and clays deposited on decaying organic marine matter, that over time, transformed into oil and natural gas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Beneath the layers of sediment is a water-deposited layer of halite, a rock salt.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The porous layers were compressed over time and forced upward.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] As it pushed upward, the salt dragged surrounding sediments into salt dome formations, often trapping oil and gas that seeped from the surrounding porous sands.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The thick, rich, sometimes black, surface soil is suitable for rice farming in suburban outskirts where the city continues to grow.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Houston area has over 150 active faults (estimated to be 300 active faults) with an aggregate length of up to 310 miles (500 km), including the Long Point–Eureka Heights fault system which runs through the center of the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Land in some areas southeast of Houston is sinking because water has been pumped out of the ground for many years.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] It may be associated with slip along the faults; however, the slippage is slow and not considered an earthquake, where stationary faults must slip suddenly enough to create seismic waves.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] These faults also tend to move at a smooth rate in what is termed "fault creep", which further reduces the risk of an earthquake.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The city of Houston was incorporated in 1837 and adopted a ward system of representation shortly afterward, in 1840.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The six original wards of Houston are the progenitors of the 11 modern-day geographically oriented Houston City Council districts, though the city abandoned the ward system in 1905 in favor of a commission government, and, later, the existing mayor–council government.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Locations in Houston are generally classified as either being inside or outside the Interstate 610 loop.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The "Inner Loop" encompasses a 97-square-mile (250 km2) area which includes Downtown, pre–World War II residential neighborhoods and streetcar suburbs, and newer high-density apartment and townhouse developments.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Outside the loop, the city's typology is more suburban, though many major business districts—such as Uptown, Westchase, and the Energy Corridor—lie well outside the urban core.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In addition to Interstate 610, two additional loop highways encircle the city: Beltway 8, with a radius of approximately 10 miles (16 km) from Downtown, and State Highway 99 (the Grand Parkway), with a radius of 25 miles (40 km).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Approximately 470,000 people lived within the Interstate 610 loop, while 1.65 million lived between Interstate 610 and Beltway 8 and 2.25 million lived within Harris County outside Beltway 8 in 2015.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Though Houston is the largest city in the United States without formal zoning regulations, it has developed similarly to other Sun Belt cities because the city's land use regulations and legal covenants have played a similar role.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Regulations include mandatory lot size for single-family houses and requirements that parking be available to tenants and customers.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 1998, Houston relaxed its mandatory lot sizes from 5,000 square feet to 3,500 square feet, which spurred housing construction in the city dramatically.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Such restrictions have had mixed results.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Though some have blamed the city's low density, urban sprawl, and lack of pedestrian-friendliness on these policies, others have credited the city's land use patterns with providing significant affordable housing, sparing Houston the worst effects of the 2008 real estate crisis.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The city issued 42,697 building permits in 2008 and was ranked first in the list of healthiest housing markets for 2009.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 2019, home sales reached a new record of $30 billion.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In referendums in 1948, 1962, and 1993, voters rejected efforts to establish separate residential and commercial land-use districts.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston had the fifth-tallest skyline in North America (after New York City, Chicago, Toronto and Miami) and 36th-tallest in the world in 2015.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] A seven-mile (11 km) system of tunnels and skywalks links Downtown buildings containing shops and restaurants, enabling pedestrians to avoid summer heat and rain while walking between buildings.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In the 1960s, Downtown Houston consisted of a collection of mid-rise office structures.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Downtown was on the threshold of an energy industry–led boom in 1970.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] A succession of skyscrapers was built throughout the 1970s—many by real estate developer Gerald D.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Hines—culminating with Houston's tallest skyscraper, the 75-floor, 1,002-foot (305 m)-tall JPMorgan Chase Tower (formerly the Texas Commerce Tower), completed in 1982.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] It is the tallest structure in Texas, 19th tallest building in the United States, and was previously 85th-tallest skyscraper in the world, based on highest architectural feature.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 1983, the 71-floor, 992-foot (302 m)-tall Wells Fargo Plaza (formerly Allied Bank Plaza) was completed, becoming the second-tallest building in Houston and Texas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Based on highest architectural feature, it is the 21st-tallest in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 2007, Downtown had over 43 million square feet (4,000,000 m2) of office space.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Centered on Post Oak Boulevard and Westheimer Road, the Uptown District boomed during the 1970s and early 1980s when a collection of midrise office buildings, hotels, and retail developments appeared along I-610 West.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Uptown became one of the most prominent instances of an edge city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The tallest building in Uptown is the 64-floor, 901-foot (275 m)-tall, Philip Johnson and John Burgee designed landmark Williams Tower (known as the Transco Tower until 1999).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] At the time of construction, it was believed to be the world's tallest skyscraper outside a central business district.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The new 20-story Skanska building and BBVA Compass Plaza are the newest office buildings built in Uptown after 30 years.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Uptown District is also home to buildings designed by noted architects I.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, a mini-boom of midrise and highrise residential tower construction occurred, with several over 30 stories tall.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Since 2000 over 30 skyscrapers have been developed in Houston; all told, 72 high-rises tower over the city, which adds up to about 8,300 units.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In 2002, Uptown had more than 23 million square feet (2,100,000 m2) of office space with 16 million square feet (1,500,000 m2) of class A office space.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston's climate is classified as humid subtropical (*Cfa* in the Köppen climate classification system), typical of the Southern United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] While not in Tornado Alley, like much of Northern Texas, spring supercell thunderstorms sometimes bring tornadoes to the area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Prevailing winds are from the south and southeast during most of the year, which bring heat and tropical moisture from the nearby Gulf of Mexico and Galveston Bay.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] During the summer, temperatures reach or exceed 90 °F (32 °C) an average of 106.5 days per year, including a majority of days from June to September.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Additionally, an average of 4.6 days per year reach or exceed 100 °F (37.8 °C).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston's characteristic subtropical humidity often results in a higher apparent temperature, and summer mornings average over 90% relative humidity.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Air conditioning is ubiquitous in Houston; in 1981, annual spending on electricity for interior cooling exceeded $600 million (equivalent to $2.12 billion in 2025), and by the late 1990s, approximately 90% of Houston homes featured air conditioning systems.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The record highest temperature recorded in Houston is 109 °F (43 °C) at Bush Intercontinental Airport, on four occasions: September 4, 2000; August 27, 2011; and August 24 and August 27, 2023.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston has mild winters, with occasional cold spells.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In January, the normal mean temperature at George Bush Intercontinental Airport is 53 °F (12 °C), with an average of 13 days per year with a low at or below 32 °F (0 °C), occurring on average between December 3 and February 20, allowing for a growing season of 286 days.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Twenty-first century snow events in Houston include a storm on December 24, 2004, which saw 1 inch (3 cm) of snow accumulate in parts of the metro area, and an event on December 7, 2017, which precipitated 0.7 inches (2 cm) of snowfall.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Snowfalls of at least 1 inch (2.5 cm) on both December 10, 2008, and December 4, 2009, marked the first time measurable snowfall had occurred in two consecutive years in the city's recorded history.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Overall, Houston has seen measurable snowfall 38 times between 1895 and 2018.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] On February 14 and 15, 1895, Houston received 20 inches (51 cm) of snow, its largest snowfall from one storm on record.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The coldest temperature officially recorded in Houston was 5 °F (−15 °C) on January 18, 1930.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The last time Houston saw single digit temperatures was on December 23, 1989.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The temperature dropped to 7 °F (−14 °C) at Bush Airport, marking the coldest temperature ever recorded there.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] 1.7 inches of snow fell at George Bush Intercontinental Airport the previous day.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston generally receives ample rainfall, averaging about 49.8 in (1,260 mm) annually based on records between 1981 and 2010.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Many parts of the city have a high risk of localized flooding due to flat topography, ubiquitous low-permeability clay-silt prairie soils, and inadequate infrastructure.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] During the mid-2010s, Greater Houston experienced consecutive major flood events in 2015 ("Memorial Day"), 2016 ("Tax Day"), and 2017 (Hurricane Harvey).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Overall, there have been more casualties and property loss from floods in Houston than in any other locality in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The majority of rainfall occurs between April and October (the wet season of Southeast Texas), when the moisture from the Gulf of Mexico evaporates extensively over the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Houston has excessive ozone levels and is routinely ranked among the most ozone-polluted cities in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Ground-level ozone, or smog, is Houston's predominant air pollution problem, with the American Lung Association rating the metropolitan area's ozone level twelfth on the "Most Polluted Cities by Ozone" in 2017, after major cities such as Los Angeles, Phoenix, New York City, and Denver.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The industries along the ship channel are a major cause of the city's air pollution.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The rankings are in terms of peak-based standards, focusing strictly on the worst days of the year; the average ozone levels in Houston are lower than what is seen in most other areas of the country, as dominant winds ensure clean, marine air from the Gulf.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Excessive man-made emissions in the Houston area led to a persistent increase of atmospheric carbon dioxide over the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Such an increase, often regarded as "CO2 urban dome", is driven by a combination of strong emissions and stagnant atmospheric conditions.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Moreover, Houston is the only metropolitan area with less than ten million citizens where such a CO2 dome can be detected by satellites.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Because of Houston's proximity to the Gulf Coast, the city is prone to flooding from heavy rains; the most notable flooding events include Tropical Storm Allison in 2001 and Hurricane Harvey in 2017, along with most recent Tropical Storm Imelda in 2019 and Tropical Storm Beta in 2020.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In response to Hurricane Harvey, Mayor Sylvester Turner of Houston initiated plans to require developers to build homes that will be less susceptible to flooding by raising them two feet above the 500-year floodplain.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Hurricane Harvey damaged hundreds of thousands of homes and dumped trillions of gallons of water into the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In places this led to feet of standing water that blocked streets and flooded homes.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] The Houston City Council passed this regulation in 2018 with a vote of 9–7.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Had these floodplain development rules had been in place all along, it is estimated that 84% of homes in the 100-year and 500-year floodplains would have been spared damage.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In a recent case testing these regulations, near the Brickhouse Gulley, an old golf course that long served as a floodplain and reservoir for floodwaters, announced a change of heart toward intensifying development.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] A nationwide developer, Meritage Homes, bought the land and planned to develop the 500-year floodplain into 900 new residential homes.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Their plan would bring in $360 million in revenue and boost city population and tax revenue.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In order to meet the new floodplain regulations, the developers needed to elevate the lowest floors two feet above the 500-year floodplain, equivalent to five or six feet above the 100-year base flood elevation, and build a channel to direct stormwater runoff toward detention basins.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Before Hurricane Harvey, the city had bought $10.7 million in houses in this area specifically to take them out of danger.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] In addition to developing new streets and single-family housing within a floodplain, a flowing flood-water stream termed a floodway runs through the development area, a most dangerous place to encounter during any future flooding event.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p01] Harris County, like other more rural counties, cannot direct developers where to build or not build via land use controls such as a zoning ordinance by Texas law, and instead can only impose general floodplain regulations for enforcement during subdivision approvals and building permit approvals.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The 2020 U.S. census determined Houston had a population of 2,304,580.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] An estimated 600,000 undocumented immigrants resided in the Houston area in 2017, comprising nearly 9% of the city's metropolitan population.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] At the 2010 United States census, Houston had a population of 2,100,263 residents, up from the city's 2,396 at the 1850 census.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The median age was 33.1, up from 32.9 in 2017 and down from 33.5 in 2014; the city's youthfulness has been attributed to an influx of an African American New Great Migration, Hispanic and Latino American, and Asian immigrants into Texas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] For every 100 females, there were 98.5 males.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] An estimated 42.3% of Houstonians owned housing units, with an average of 2.65 people per household.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The median monthly owner costs with a mortgage were $1,646, and $536 without a mortgage.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The median household income in 2019 was $52,338 and 20.1% of Houstonians lived at or below the poverty line.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Rice University Kinder Institute for Urban Research, a think tank, has described Greater Houston as "one of the most ethnically and culturally diverse metropolitan areas in the country".
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston's diversity, historically fueled by large waves of Hispanic and Latino Americans, and Asian immigrants, has been attributed to its relatively lower cost of living compared to most major cities, strong job market, and role as a hub for refugee resettlement.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston has long been known as a popular destination for African Americans due to the city's well-established and influential African American community.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston has become known as a black mecca akin to Atlanta because it is a major living destination for black professionals and entrepreneurs.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston area is home to the largest African American community in Texas and west of the Mississippi River.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Census Bureau, non-Hispanic whites made up 23.3% of the population of Houston proper, Hispanics and Latino Americans 45.8%, blacks or African Americans 22.4%, and Asian Americans 6.5%.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2018, non-Hispanic whites made up 20.7% of the population, Hispanics or Latino Americans 44.9%, blacks or African Americans 30.3%, and Asian Americans 8.2%.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The largest Hispanic or Latino American ethnic groups in the city were Mexican Americans (31.6%), Puerto Ricans (0.8%), and Cuban Americans (0.8%) in 2018.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] As documented, Houston has a higher proportion of minorities than non-Hispanic whites; in 2010, whites (including Hispanic whites) made up 57.6% of the city of Houston's population; 24.6% of the total population was non-Hispanic white.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Blacks or African Americans made up 22.5% of Houston's population, American Indians made up 0.3% of the population, Asians made up 6.9% (1.7% Vietnamese, 1.3% Chinese, 1.3% Indian, 0.9% Pakistani, 0.4% Filipino, 0.3% Korean, 0.1% Japanese) and Pacific Islanders made up 0.1%.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Individuals from some other race made up 15.69% of the city's population.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Individuals from two or more races made up 2.1% of the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] At the 2000 U.S. census, the racial makeup of the city was 49.3% White, 25.3% black or African American, 5.3% Asian, 0.7% American Indian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 16.5% from some other race, and 3.1% from two or more races.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In addition, Hispanics and Latinos of any race made up 37.4% of Houston's population in 2000, while non-Hispanic whites made up 30.8%.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The proportion of non-Hispanic whites in Houston has decreased significantly since 1970, when it was 62.4%.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is home to one of the largest LGBT communities and pride parades in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2018, the city scored a 70 out of 100 for LGBT friendliness.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Jordan Blum of the *Houston Chronicle* stated levels of LGBT acceptance and discrimination varied in 2016 due to some of the region's traditionally conservative culture.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Before the 1970s, the city's gay bars were spread around Downtown Houston and what is now midtown Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] LGBT Houstonians needed to have a place to socialize after the closing of the gay bars.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] They began going to Art Wren, a 24-hour restaurant in Montrose.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] LGBT community members were attracted to Montrose as a neighborhood after encountering it while patronizing Art Wren, and they began to gentrify the neighborhood and assist its native inhabitants with property maintenance.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Within Montrose, new gay bars began to open.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] By 1985, the flavor and politics of the neighborhood were heavily influenced by the LGBT community, and in 1990, according to Hill, 19% of Montrose residents identified as LGBT.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Paul Broussard was murdered in Montrose in 1991.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Before the legalization of same-sex marriage in the United States the marriage of Billie Ert and Antonio Molina, considered the first same-sex marriage in Texas history, took place on October 5, 1972.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston elected the first openly lesbian mayor of a major city in 2009, and she served until 2016.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] During her tenure she authorized the Houston Equal Rights Ordinance which was intended to improve anti-discrimination coverage based on sexual orientation and gender identity in the city, specifically in areas such as housing and occupation where no anti-discrimination policy existed.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston and its metropolitan area are the third-most religious and Christian area by percentage of population in the United States, and second in Texas behind the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Historically, Houston has been a center of Protestant Christianity, being part of the Bible Belt.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965 removed the quotas, allowing for the growth of other religions.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] According to a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center, 73% of the population of the Houston area identified themselves as Christians, about 50% of whom claimed Protestant affiliations and about 19% claimed Roman Catholic affiliations.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Nationwide, about 71% of respondents identified as Christians.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] About 20% of Houston-area residents claimed no religious affiliation, compared to about 23% nationwide.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The same study says area residents who identify with other religions (including Judaism, Buddhism, Islam, and Hinduism) collectively made up about 7% of the area population.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2020, the Public Religion Research Institute estimated 40% were Protestant and 29% Catholic; overall, Christianity represented 72% of the population.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Non-denominational Protestants, the Disciples of Christ, Christian Churches and Churches of Christ, and the Churches of Christ numbered 723,603 altogether according to this study.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Lakewood Church in Houston, led by Pastor Joel Osteen, is the largest church in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] A megachurch, it had 44,800 weekly attendees in 2010, up from 11,000 weekly in 2000.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Since 2005, it has occupied the former Compaq Center sports stadium.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In September 2010, *Outreach* magazine published a list of the 100 largest Christian churches in the United States, and on the list were the following Houston-area churches: Lakewood, Second Baptist Church Houston, Woodlands Church, Church Without Walls, and First Baptist Church.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] According to the list, Houston and Dallas were tied as the second-most popular city for megachurches.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Galveston-Houston, the largest Catholic jurisdiction in Texas and fifth-largest in the United States, was established in 1847.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Galveston-Houston claimed approximately 1.7 million Catholics within its boundaries as of 2019.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Its co-cathedral is located within the Houston city limits, while the diocesan see is in Galveston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Other prominent Catholic jurisdictions include the Eastern Catholic Ruthenian Greek Catholic Church and Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church as well as the Personal Ordinariate of the Chair of Saint Peter, whose cathedral is also in Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] A variety of Eastern and Oriental Orthodox churches can be found in Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Immigrants from Eastern Europe, the Middle East, Ethiopia, India, and other areas have added to Houston's Eastern and Oriental Orthodox population.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] As of 2011 in the entire state, 32,000 people actively attended Orthodox churches.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2013 Father John Whiteford, the pastor of St.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Jonah Orthodox Church near Spring, stated there were about 6,000-9,000 Eastern Orthodox Christians in Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Association of Religion Data Archives numbered 16,526 Eastern and Oriental Orthodox Houstonians in 2020.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The most prominent Eastern and Oriental Orthodox jurisdictions are the Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America, the Antiochian Orthodox Archdiocese of North America, the Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria, the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church, and the Armenian Apostolic Church.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston's Jewish community, estimated at 47,000 in 2001, has been present in the city since the 1800s.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houstonian Jews have origins from throughout the United States, Israel, Mexico, Russia, and other places.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] As of 2016, over 40 synagogues were in Greater Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The largest synagogues are Congregation Beth Yeshurun, a Conservative Jewish temple, and the Reform Jewish congregations Beth Israel and Emanu-El.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] According to a study in 2016 by Berman Jewish DataBank, 51,000 Jews lived in the area, an increase of 4,000 since 2001.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston has a large and diverse Muslim community; it is the largest in Texas and the Southern United States, as of 2012.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] It is estimated that Muslims made up 1.2% of Houston's population.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] As of 2016, Muslims in the Houston area included South Asians, Middle Easterners, Africans, Turks, and Indonesians, as well as a growing population of Latino Muslim converts.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2000 there were over 41 mosques and storefront religious centers, with the largest being the *Al-Noor* Mosque (Mosque of Light) of the Islamic Society of Greater Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Hindu, Sikh, and Buddhist communities form a growing sector of the religious demographic after Judaism and Islam.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Of the irreligious community 16% practiced nothing in particular, 3% were agnostic, and 2% were atheist in 2014.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is recognized worldwide for its energy industry—particularly for oil and natural gas—as well as for biomedical research and aeronautics.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Renewable energy sources—wind and solar—are also growing economic bases in the city, and the City Government purchases 90% of its annual 1 TWh power mostly from wind, and some from solar.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Since the 2020s Houston has become a growing hub for technology startup firms and is the fastest growing sector of the city's economy.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Major technology and software companies within Greater Houston include Crown Castle, KBR, FlightAware, Cybersoft, Houston Wire & Cable, and HostGator.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Aylo, Go Daddy, and ByteDance have offices in the Houston area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] On April 4, 2022, Hewlett Packard Enterprise relocated its global headquarters from California to the Greater Houston area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Ship Channel is also a large part of Houston's economic base.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Because of these strengths, Houston is designated as a global city by the Globalization and World Cities Study Group and Network and global management consulting firm A.T.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston area is the top U.S. market for exports, surpassing New York City in 2013, according to data released by the U.S.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Department of Commerce's International Trade Administration.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2012, the Houston–The Woodlands–Sugar Land area recorded $110.3 billion in merchandise exports.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Petroleum products, chemicals, and oil and gas extraction equipment accounted for roughly two-thirds of the metropolitan area's exports last year.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The top three destinations for exports were Mexico, Canada, and Brazil.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston area is a leading center for building oilfield equipment.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Much of its success as a petrochemical complex is due to its busy ship channel, the Port of Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In the United States, the port ranks first in international commerce and 16th among the largest ports in the world.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Unlike most places, high oil and gasoline prices are beneficial for Houston's economy, as many of its residents are employed in the energy industry.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is the beginning or end point of numerous oil, gas, and products pipelines.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston–The Woodlands–Sugar Land metro area's gross domestic product (GDP) in 2022 was $633 billion, making it the seventh-largest of any metropolitan area in the United States and larger than Iran's, Colombia's, or the United Arab Emirates' GDP.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Only 27 countries other than the United States have a gross domestic product exceeding Houston's regional gross area product (GAP).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The University of Houston System's annual impact on the Houston area's economy equates to that of a major corporation: $1.1 billion in new funds attracted annually to the Houston area, $3.13 billion in total economic benefit, and 24,000 local jobs generated.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] This is in addition to the 12,500 new graduates the U.H.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] System produces every year who enter the workforce in Houston and throughout Texas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] These degree-holders tend to stay in Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] After five years, 80.5% of graduates are still living and working in the region.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Ninety-one foreign governments have established consular offices in Houston's metropolitan area, the third-highest in the nation.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Forty foreign governments maintain trade and commercial offices here with 23 active foreign chambers of commerce and trade associations.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Twenty-five foreign banks representing 13 nations operate in Houston, providing financial assistance to the international community.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2013, Houston was identified as the number one U.S. city for job creation by the U.S.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Bureau of Labor Statistics after it was not only the first major city to regain all the jobs lost in the preceding economic downturn, but also after the crash, more than two jobs were added for every one lost.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Economist and vice president of research at the Greater Houston Partnership Patrick Jankowski attributed Houston's success to the ability of the region's real estate and energy industries to learn from historical mistakes.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Furthermore, Jankowski stated that "more than 100 foreign-owned companies relocated, expanded or started new businesses in Houston" between 2008 and 2010, and this openness to external business boosted job creation during a period when domestic demand was problematically low.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Located in the American South, Houston is a diverse city with a large and growing international community.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Greater Houston metropolitan area is home to an estimated 1.1 million (21.4 percent) residents who were born outside the United States, with nearly two-thirds of the area's foreign-born population from south of the United States–Mexico border since 2009.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Additionally, more than one in five foreign-born residents are from Asia.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city is home to the nation's third-largest concentration of consular offices, representing 92 countries.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Many annual events celebrate the diverse cultures of Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The largest and longest-running is the annual Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo, held over 20 days from early to late March, and is the largest annual livestock show and rodeo in the world.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Another large celebration is the annual night-time Houston Gay Pride Parade, held at the end of June.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Other notable annual events include the Houston Greek Festival, Art Car Parade, the Houston Auto Show, the Houston International Festival, and the Bayou City Art Festival, which is considered to be one of the top five art festivals in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is highly regarded for its diverse food and restaurant culture.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston received the official nickname of "Space City" in 1967 because it is the location of NASA's Lyndon B.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Other nicknames often used by locals include "Bayou City", "Clutch City", "Crush City", "Magnolia City", "H-Town", and "Culinary Capital of the South".
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Theater District, in Downtown, is home to nine major performing arts organizations and six performance halls.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] It is the second-largest concentration of theater seats in a Downtown area in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is one of the few United States cities with permanent, professional, resident companies in all major performing arts disciplines: opera (Houston Grand Opera), ballet (Houston Ballet), music (Houston Symphony Orchestra), and theater (The Alley Theatre, Theatre Under the Stars).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is also home to folk artists, art groups and various small progressive arts organizations.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston attracts many touring Broadway acts, concerts, shows, and exhibitions for a variety of interests.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Facilities in the Theater District include the Jones Hall—home of the Houston Symphony Orchestra and Society for the Performing Arts—and the Hobby Center for the Performing Arts.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Museum District's cultural institutions and exhibits attract more than 7 million visitors a year.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Notable facilities include The Museum of Fine Arts, the Houston Museum of Natural Science, the Contemporary Arts Museum Houston, the Station Museum of Contemporary Art, the Holocaust Museum Houston, the Children's Museum of Houston, and the Houston Zoo.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Located near the Museum District are The Menil Collection, Rothko Chapel, the Moody Center for the Arts and the Byzantine Fresco Chapel Museum.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Bayou Bend is a 14-acre (5.7 ha) facility of the Museum of Fine Arts that houses one of America's most prominent collections of decorative art, paintings, and furniture.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Bayou Bend is the former home of Houston philanthropist Ima Hogg.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The National Museum of Funeral History is in Houston near the George Bush Intercontinental Airport.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The museum houses the original Popemobile used by Pope John Paul II in the 1980s along with numerous hearses, embalming displays, and information on famous funerals.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Venues across Houston regularly host local and touring rock, blues, country, dubstep, and Tejano musical acts.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] While Houston has never been widely known for its music scene, Houston hip hop has become a significant, independent music scene that is influential nationwide.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is the birthplace of the chopped and screwed remixing technique in hip-hop, which was pioneered by DJ Screw from the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Some other notable hip-hop artists from the area include Destiny's Child, Don Toliver, Slim Thug, Paul Wall, Mike Jones, Bun B, Geto Boys, Trae tha Truth, Kirko Bangz, Z-Ro, South Park Mexican, Travis Scott and Megan Thee Stallion.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Theater District is a 17-block area in the center of Downtown Houston that is home to the Bayou Place entertainment complex, restaurants, movies, plazas, and parks.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Bayou Place is a large multilevel building containing full-service restaurants, bars, live music, billiards, and Sundance Cinema.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Bayou Music Center stages live concerts, stage plays, and stand-up comedy.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Space Center Houston is the official visitors' center of NASA's Lyndon B.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Space Center has many interactive exhibits including Moon rocks, a Space Shuttle simulator, and presentations about the history of NASA's crewed space flight program.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Other tourist attractions include the Galleria (Texas's largest shopping mall, in the Uptown District), Old Market Square, the Downtown Aquarium, and Sam Houston Race Park.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston's current Chinatown and the Mahatma Gandhi District are two major ethnic enclaves, reflecting Houston's multicultural makeup.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Restaurants, bakeries, traditional-clothing boutiques, and specialty shops can be found in both areas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is home to 337 parks, including Hermann Park, Terry Hershey Park, Lake Houston Park, Memorial Park, Tranquility Park, Sesquicentennial Park, Discovery Green, Buffalo Bayou Park and Sam Houston Park.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Within Hermann Park are the Houston Zoo and the Houston Museum of Natural Science.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Sam Houston Park contains restored and reconstructed homes which were originally built between 1823 and 1905.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Of the 10 most populous U.S. cities, Houston has the largest total area of parks and green space, 56,405 acres (228 km2).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city also has over 200 additional green spaces—totaling over 19,600 acres (79 km2) that are managed by the city—including the Houston Arboretum and Nature Center.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Lee and Joe Jamail Skatepark is a public skatepark owned and operated by the city of Houston, and is one of the largest skateparks in Texas consisting of a 30,000 ft2 (2,800 m2) in-ground facility.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Hines Waterwall Park in the Uptown District of the city serves as a popular tourist attraction and for weddings and various celebrations.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] A 2011 study by Walk Score ranked Houston the 23rd most walkable of the 50 largest cities in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston has sports teams for every major professional league except the National Hockey League.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Astros are a Major League Baseball expansion team formed in 1962 (known as the "Colt .45s" until 1965) that have won the World Series in 2017 and 2022 and appeared in it in 2005, 2019, and 2021.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] It is the only MLB team to have won pennants in both modern leagues.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Rockets are a National Basketball Association franchise based in the city since 1971.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] They have won two NBA Championships, one in 1994 and another in 1995, under star players Hakeem Olajuwon, Otis Thorpe, Clyde Drexler, Vernon Maxwell, and Kenny Smith.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Texans are a National Football League expansion team formed in 2002.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Dynamo is a Major League Soccer franchise that has been based in Houston since 2006, winning two MLS Cup titles in 2006 and 2007.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Dash team plays in the National Women's Soccer League, who won their first title in 2020.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Gamblers are a UFL team that began play in 2024.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] They were previously in the XFL before it was announced they were moving to the UFL in 2024.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Daikin Park (home of the Astros) and Toyota Center (home of the Rockets), are in Downtown Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston has the NFL's first retractable-roof stadium with natural grass, NRG Stadium (home of the Texans).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Daikin Park is also a retractable-roof stadium.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Toyota Center also has the largest screen for an indoor arena in the United States built to coincide with the arena's hosting of the 2013 NBA All-Star Game.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Shell Energy Stadium is a soccer-specific stadium for the Houston Dynamo, Houston Gamblers, the Texas Southern Tigers football team, and Houston Dash, in East Downtown.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Aveva Stadium (home of the SaberCats) is in south Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In addition, NRG Astrodome was the first indoor stadium in the world, built in 1965.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Other sports facilities include the Fertitta Center (Houston Cougars basketball), Rice Stadium (Rice Owls football), and NRG Arena.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] TDECU Stadium is where the University of Houston's Cougars football team plays.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city won its first baseball championship during the 2017 event and won again 5 years later.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] NRG Stadium hosted Super Bowl LI on February 5, 2017.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston will host multiple matches during the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city has hosted several major professional and college sporting events, including the annual Houston Open golf tournament.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston hosts the annual Houston College Classic baseball tournament every February, and the Texas Kickoff and Bowl in September and December, respectively.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Grand Prix of Houston, an annual auto race on the IndyCar Series circuit was held on a 1.7-mile temporary street circuit in NRG Park.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The October 2013 event was held using a tweaked version of the 2006–2007 course.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The event had a five-year race contract through 2017 with IndyCar.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In motorcycling, the Astrodome hosted an AMA Supercross Championship round from 1974 to 2003 and the NRG Stadium since 2003.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city of Houston has a strong mayoral form of municipal government.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is a home rule city and all municipal elections in Texas are nonpartisan.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city's elected officials are the mayor, city controller and 16 members of the Houston City Council.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The current mayor of Houston is John Whitmire, a Democrat elected on a nonpartisan ballot.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston's mayor serves as the city's chief administrator, executive officer, and official representative, and is responsible for the general management of the city and for seeing all laws and ordinances are enforced.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The original city council line-up of 14 members (nine district-based and five at-large positions) was based on a U.S.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Justice Department mandate which took effect in 1979.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] At-large council members represent the entire city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Under the city charter, once the population in the city limits exceeded 2.1 million residents, two additional districts were to be added.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city of Houston's official 2010 census count was 600 shy of the required number; however, as the city was expected to grow beyond 2.1 million shortly thereafter, the two additional districts were added for, and the positions filled during, the August 2011 elections.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city controller is elected independently of the mayor and council.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The controller's duties are to certify available funds prior to committing such funds and processing disbursements.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city's fiscal year begins on July 1 and ends on June 30.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Chris Brown is the city controller, serving his first term as of January 2016.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] As the result of a 2015 referendum in Houston, a mayor is elected for a four-year term and can be elected to as many as two consecutive terms.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The term limits were spearheaded in 1991 by conservative political activist Clymer Wright.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] During 1991–2015, the city controller and city council members were subjected to a two-year, three-term limitation–the 2015 referendum amended term limits to two four-year terms.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is considered to be a politically divided city whose balance of power often sways between Republicans and Democrats.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] According to the 2005 Houston Area Survey, 68 percent of non-Hispanic whites in Harris County are declared or favor Republicans while 89 percent of non-Hispanic blacks in the area are declared or favor Democrats.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] About 62 percent of Hispanics (of any nationality) in the area are declared or favor Democrats.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The city has often been known to be the most politically diverse city in Texas, a state known for being generally conservative.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] As a result, the city is often a contested area in statewide elections.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2009, Houston became the first U.S. city with a population over 1 million citizens to elect a gay mayor, by electing Annise Parker.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Texas has banned sanctuary cities but Houston mayor Sylvester Turner said that Houston would not assist ICE agents with immigration raids.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston's crime rate is one of the top three in Texas and notably higher than the national average.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston's murder rate jumped significantly since 2020.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2021, nearly 500 people were murdered in the city which was almost double the murdered count in 2019.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Rising gang activity is blamed for the increased crime rates in the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston leaders are continually discussing and implementing strategies to combat crime in the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is a significant hub for trafficking of cocaine, cannabis, heroin, MDMA, and methamphetamine due to its size and proximity to major illegal drug exporting nations.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In the early 1970s, Houston, Pasadena and several coastal towns were the site of the Houston mass murders, which at the time were the deadliest case of serial killing in American history.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 1853, the first execution in Houston took place in public at Founder's Cemetery in the Fourth Ward; initially, the cemetery was the execution site, but post-1868 executions took place in the jail facilities.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In 2023, the city of Houston made enforcement of an anti-food sharing ordinance a priority.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] This has resulted in volunteers receiving over 80 tickets, and a federal lawsuit to be filed against the city of Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Nineteen school districts exist within the city of Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Independent School District (HISD) is the seventh-largest school district in the United States and the largest in Texas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] HISD has over 100 campuses that serve as magnet or vanguard schools—specializing in such disciplines as health professions, visual and performing arts, and the sciences.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] There are also many charter schools that are run separately from school districts.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In addition, some public school districts also have their own charter schools.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston area encompasses more than 300 private schools, many of which are accredited by Texas Private School Accreditation Commission recognized agencies.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Greater Houston metropolitan area's independent schools offer education from a variety of different religious as well as secular viewpoints.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Greater Houston area's Catholic schools are operated by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Galveston-Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The University of Houston (UH) is a research university and the flagship institution of the University of Houston System.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The third-largest university in Texas, the University of Houston has nearly 44,000 students on its 667-acre (270-hectare) campus in the Third Ward.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The University of Houston–Clear Lake and the University of Houston–Downtown are stand-alone universities within the University of Houston System; they are not branch campuses of the University of Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Slightly west of the University of Houston is Texas Southern University (TSU), one of the largest historically black universities in the United States with approximately 10,000 students.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Texas Southern University is the first state university in Houston, founded in 1927.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Several private institutions of higher learning are within the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Rice University, the most selective university in Texas and one of the most selective in the United States, is a private, secular institution with a high level of research activity.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Founded in 1912, Rice's historic, heavily wooded 300-acre (120-hectare) campus, adjacent to Hermann Park and the Texas Medical Center, hosts approximately 4,000 undergraduate and 3,000 post-graduate students.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] To the north in Neartown, the University of St.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Thomas, founded in 1947, is Houston's only Catholic university.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Thomas provides a liberal arts curriculum for roughly 3,000 students at its historic 19-block campus along Montrose Boulevard.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] In southwest Houston, Houston Christian University (formerly Houston Baptist University), founded in 1960, offers bachelor's and graduate degrees at its Sharpstown campus.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The school is affiliated with the Baptist General Convention of Texas and has a student population of approximately 3,000.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Three community college districts have campuses in and around Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Community College System (HCC) serves most of Houston proper; its main campus and headquarters are in Midtown.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Suburban northern and western parts of the metropolitan area are served by various campuses of the Lone Star College System, while the southeastern portion of Houston is served by San Jacinto College, and a northeastern portion is served by Lee College.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston Community College and Lone Star College systems are among the 10 largest institutions of higher learning in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston also hosts a number of graduate schools in law and healthcare.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The University of Houston Law Center and Thurgood Marshall School of Law at Texas Southern University are public, ABA-accredited law schools, while the South Texas College of Law, in Downtown, serves as a private, independent alternative.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Texas Medical Center is home to a high density of health professions schools, including two medical schools: McGovern Medical School, part of The University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston, and Baylor College of Medicine, a highly selective private institution.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Prairie View A&M University's nursing school is in the Texas Medical Center.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Additionally, both Texas Southern University and the University of Houston have pharmacy schools, and the University of Houston hosts a medical school and a college of optometry.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] KTRK-TV, KTXH, KRIV, KIAH, KXLN-DT, KTMD-TV, KPXB-TV, KYAZ and KFTH-DT operate as owned-and-operated stations of their networks.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Houston–The Woodlands–Sugar Land metropolitan area is served by one public television station and two public radio stations.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] KUHT channel 8 (*Houston Public Media*) is a PBS member station and is the first public television station in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston Public Radio is listener-funded and comprises one NPR member station, KUHF (*News 88.7*).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The University of Houston System owns and holds broadcasting licenses to KUHT and KUHF.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The stations broadcast from the Melcher Center for Public Broadcasting on the campus of the University of Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston additionally is served by the Pacifica Foundation public radio station KPFT.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston and its metropolitan area are served by the *Houston Chronicle*, its only major daily newspaper with wide distribution.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Hearst Communications, which owns and operates the *Houston Chronicle*, bought the assets of the *Houston Post*—its long-time rival and main competition—when *Houston Post* ceased operations in 1995.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The *Houston Post* was owned by the family of former Lieutenant Governor Bill Hobby of Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The only other major publication to serve the city is the *Houston Press*—which was a free alternative weekly newspaper before the destruction caused by Hurricane Harvey resulted in the publication switching to an online-only format on November 2, 2017.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Other notable publications include *Houston Forward Times*, *OutSmart*, and *La Voz de Houston*.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] *Houston Forward Times* is one of the largest black-owned newspapers in the metropolitan area and owned by Forward Times Publishing Company.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] *La Voz de Houston* is the *Houston Chronicle*'s Spanish-language newspaper and the largest in the area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Houston is the seat of the Texas Medical Center, which is the largest medical center in the world, and which describes itself as containing the world's largest concentration of research and healthcare institutions.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] All 49 member institutions of the Texas Medical Center are non-profit organizations.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] They provide patient and preventive care, research, education, and local, national, and international community well-being.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Employing more than 73,600 people, institutions at the medical center include 13 hospitals and two specialty institutions, two medical schools, four nursing schools, and schools of dentistry, public health, pharmacy, and virtually all health-related careers.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] It is where one of the first—and still the largest—air emergency service, Life Flight, was created, and an inter-institutional transplant program was developed.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Around 2007, more heart surgeries were performed at the Texas Medical Center than anywhere else in the world.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The Menninger Clinic, a psychiatric treatment center, is affiliated with Baylor College of Medicine and the Houston Methodist Hospital System.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] With hospital locations nationwide and headquarters in Houston, the Triumph Healthcare hospital system was the third largest long term acute care provider nationally in 2005.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Harris Health System (formerly Harris County Hospital District), the hospital district for Harris County, operates public hospitals (Ben Taub General Hospital and Lyndon B.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] The City of Houston Health Department also operates four clinics.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] As of 2011 the dental centers of Harris Health System take patients of ages 16 and up with patients under that age referred to the City of Houston's dental clinics.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Montgomery County Hospital District (MCHD) serves as the hospital district for Houstonians living in Montgomery County.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] Fort Bend County, in which a portion of Houston resides, does not have a hospital district.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p02] OakBend Medical Center serves as the county's charity hospital which the county contracts with.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Houston is considered an automobile-dependent city, with an estimated 77.2% of commuters driving alone to work in 2016, up from 71.7% in 1990 and 75.6% in 2009.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In 2016, another 11.4% of Houstonians carpooled to work, while 3.6% used public transit, 2.1% walked, and 0.5% bicycled.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] A commuting study estimated the median length of commute in the region was 12.2 miles (19.6 km) in 2012.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] According to the 2013 American Community Survey, the average work commute in Houston (city) takes 26.3 minutes.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] A 1999 Murdoch University study found Houston had both the lengthiest commute and lowest urban density of 13 large American cities surveyed.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Harris County is one of the largest consumers of gasoline in the United States, ranking second (behind Los Angeles County) in 2013.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Despite the region's high rate of automobile usage, attitudes towards transportation among Houstonians indicate a growing preference for walkability.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] A 2017 study by the Rice University Kinder Institute for Urban Research found 56% of Harris County residents have a preference for dense housing in a mixed-use, walkable setting as opposed to single-family housing in a low-density area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] A plurality of survey respondents also indicated traffic congestion was the most significant problem facing the metropolitan area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In addition, many households in the city of Houston have no car.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In 2015, 8.3 percent of Houston households lacked a car, which was virtually unchanged in 2016 (8.1 percent).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Houston averaged 1.59 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The eight-county Greater Houston metropolitan area contains over 25,000 miles (40,000 km) of roadway, of which 10%, or approximately 2,500 miles (4,000 km), is limited-access highway.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The Houston region's extensive freeway system handles over 40% of the regional daily vehicle miles traveled (VMT).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Arterial roads handle an additional 40% of daily VMT, while toll roads, of which Greater Houston has 180 miles (290 km), handle nearly 10%.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Greater Houston possesses a hub-and-spoke limited-access highway system, in which a number of freeways radiate outward from Downtown, with ring roads providing connections between these radial highways at intermediate distances from the city center.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The city is crossed by three Interstate highways, I-10, I-45, and I-69 (commonly known as US 59), as well as a number of other United States routes and state highways.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Major freeways in Greater Houston are often referred to by either the cardinal direction or geographic location they travel towards.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Highways that follow the cardinal convention include US 290 (*Northwest Freeway*), I-45 north of Downtown (*North Freeway*), I-10 east of Downtown *(East Freeway*), SH 288 (*South* *Freeway*), and I-69 south of Downtown (*Southwest Freeway*).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Highways that follow the location convention include Interstate 10 west of Downtown (*Katy Freeway*), Interstate 69 north of Downtown (*Eastex Freeway*), I-45 south of Downtown (*Gulf Freeway*), and SH 225 (*Pasadena Freeway*).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Three loop freeways provide north–south and east–west connectivity between Greater Houston's radial highways.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The innermost loop is I-610, commonly known as the *Inner Loop*, which encircles Downtown, the Texas Medical Center, Greenway Plaza, the cities of West University Place and Southside Place, and many core neighborhoods.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The 88-mile (142 km) Beltway 8, often referred to as *the Beltway*, forms the middle loop at a radius of roughly 10 miles (16 km).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] A third, 180-mile (290 km) loop with a radius of approximately 25 miles (40 km), SH 99 (the *Grand Parkway*), is currently under construction, with eight of eleven segments completed as of 2018.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Completed segments D through I-2 provide a continuous 123-mile (198 km) limited-access tollway connection between Sugar Land, Richmond, Katy, Cypress, Spring, Porter, New Caney, Cleveland, Dayton, Mont Belvieu, and Baytown.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] A system of toll roads, operated by the Harris County Toll Road Authority and Fort Bend County Toll Road Authority, provides additional options for regional commuters.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Westpark Tollway and Fort Bend Parkway are operated conjunctly with the Fort Bend County Toll Road Authority.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Greater Houston's freeway system is monitored by Houston TranStar, a partnership of four government agencies which is responsible for providing transportation and emergency management services to the region.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Greater Houston's arterial road network is established at the municipal level, with the City of Houston exercising planning control over both its incorporated area and extraterritorial jurisdiction.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Therefore, Houston exercises transportation planning authority over a 2,000-square-mile (5,200 km2) area over five counties, many times larger than its corporate area.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The *Major Thoroughfare and Freeway Plan*, updated annually, establishes the city's street hierarchy, identifies roadways in need of widening, and proposes new roadways in unserved areas.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Arterial roads are organized into four categories, in decreasing order of intensity: *major thoroughfares*, *transit corridor streets*, *collector streets*, and *local streets*.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Roadway classification affects anticipated traffic volumes, roadway design, and right of way breadth.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Ultimately, the system is designed to ferry traffic from neighborhood streets to major thoroughfares, which connect into the limited-access highway system.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Notable arterial roads in the region include Westheimer Road, Memorial Drive, SH 6, FM 1960, Bellaire Boulevard, and Telephone Road.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The Metropolitan Transit Authority of Harris County (METRO) provides public transportation in the form of buses, light rail, high-occupancy vehicle (HOV) lanes, and paratransit to fifteen municipalities throughout the Greater Houston area and parts of unincorporated Harris County.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] METRO's service area covers 1,303 square miles (3,370 km2) containing a population of 3.6 million.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] METRO's local bus network services approximately 275,000 riders daily with a fleet of over 1,200 buses.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The agency's 75 local routes contain nearly 8,900 stops and saw nearly 67 million boardings during the 2016 fiscal year.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] A park and ride system provides commuter bus service from 34 transit centers scattered throughout the region's suburban areas; these express buses operate independently of the local bus network and utilize the region's extensive system of HOV lanes.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Downtown and the Texas Medical Center have the highest rates of transit use in the region, largely due to the park and ride system, with nearly 60% of commuters in each district utilizing public transit to get to work.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] METRO began light rail service in 2004 with the opening of the 8-mile (13 km) north-south Red Line connecting Downtown, Midtown, the Museum District, the Texas Medical Center, and NRG Park.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In the early 2010s, two additional lines—the Green Line, servicing the East End, and the Purple Line, servicing the Third Ward—opened, and the Red Line was extended northward to Northline, bringing the total length of the system to 22.7 miles (36.5 km).
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Two light rail lines outlined in a five-line system approved by voters in a 2003 referendum have yet to be constructed.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The Uptown Line, which runs along Post Oak Boulevard in Uptown, was under construction as a bus rapid transit line—the city's first—while the University Line has been postponed indefinitely.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The light rail system saw approximately 16.8 million boardings in fiscal year 2016.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Amtrak's thrice-weekly Los Angeles–New Orleans *Sunset Limited* serves Houston at a station northwest of Downtown.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] A daily Amtrak Thruway connects Houston with Amtrak's Chicago–San Antonio *Texas Eagle* at Longview.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Houston has the largest number of bike commuters in Texas with over 160 miles of dedicated bikeways.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In 2015, Downtown Houston added a cycle track on Lamar Street, running from Sam Houston Park to Discovery Green.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Houston City Council approved the Houston Bike Plan in March 2017, at that time entering the plan into the Houston Code of Ordinances.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In August 2017, Houston City Council approved spending for construction of 13 additional miles of bike trails.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Houston had a bicycle sharing system until June 2024.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Houston Bcycle (also known as B-Cycle), a local non-profit, ran the subscription program, supplying bicycles and docking stations, while partnering with other companies to maintain the system.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The network expanded to 29 stations and 225 bicycles in 2014, registering over 43,000 checkouts of equipment during the first half of the same year.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In 2017, Bcycle logged over 142,000 check outs while expanding to 56 docking stations.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The Houston Airport System, a branch of the municipal government, oversees the operation of three major public airports in the city.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Two of these airports, George Bush Intercontinental Airport and William P.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Hobby Airport, offer commercial aviation service to a variety of domestic and international destinations and served 55 million passengers in 2016.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The third, Ellington Airport, is home to the Ellington Field Joint Reserve Base.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The Federal Aviation Administration and the state of Texas selected the Houston Airport System as "Airport of the Year" in 2005, largely due to the implementation of a $3.1 billion airport improvement program for both major airports in Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] George Bush Intercontinental Airport (IAH), 23 miles (37 km) north of Downtown Houston between Interstates 45 and 69, is the eighth busiest commercial airport in the United States (by total passengers and aircraft movements) and forty-third busiest globally.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The five-terminal, five-runway, 11,000-acre (4,500-hectare) airport served 40 million passengers in 2016, including 10 million international travelers.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In 2006, the United States Department of Transportation named IAH the fastest-growing of the top ten airports in the United States.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The Houston Air Route Traffic Control Center is at Bush Intercontinental.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Houston was the headquarters of Continental Airlines until its 2010 merger with United Airlines with headquarters in Chicago; regulatory approval for the merger was granted in October of that year.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Bush Intercontinental is currently United Airlines' second largest hub, behind O'Hare International Airport.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] United Airlines' share of the Houston Airport System's commercial aviation market was nearly 60% in 2017 with 16 million enplaned passengers.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In early 2007, Bush Intercontinental Airport was named a model "port of entry" for international travelers by U.S.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Hobby Airport (HOU), known as Houston International Airport until 1967, operates primarily short- to medium-haul domestic and international flights to 60 destinations.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] The four-runway, 1,304-acre (528-hectare) facility is approximately 7 miles (11 km) southeast of Downtown Houston.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In 2015, Southwest Airlines launched service from a new international terminal at Hobby to several destinations in Mexico, Central America, and the Caribbean.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] These were the first international flights flown from Hobby since the opening of Bush Intercontinental in 1969.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Houston's aviation history is showcased in the 1940 Air Terminal Museum in the old terminal building on the west side of the airport.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In 2009, Hobby Airport was recognized with two awards for being one of the top five performing airports globally and for customer service by Airports Council International.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] In 2022 Hobby Airport was certified as the first 5-Star Airport in North America by Skytrax.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] It became the first Airport in North America to do so and just the 16th airport worldwide to receive the accomplishment.
[src:albert-w-bally/houston-texas-p03] Houston's third municipal airport is Ellington Airport, used by the military, government (including NASA) and general aviation sectors.
